   "id": "003",
   "source": {
    "title": "DHT-SWNet: Frequency-aware ship and wake detection in multi-source optical remote sensing imagery",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.03.012",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.03.012",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "This study addresses automatic detection of ship wakes in optical remote-sensing images, aiming to improve accuracy and efficiency via joint detection of ships and Kelvin wakes. First, we construct a new Remote Sensing Ship Wake (RSSW) dataset from multi-source optical imagery and develop dedicated labeling software to ensure reliable data preparation. Second, we propose the Discrete Hartley Transform Ship Wake Network (DHT-SWNet), which integrates DHT-based frequency analysis to capture the characteristic patterns of Kelvin wake. To further enhance representation, the network adopts efficient multi-scale feature integration, strengthening learning across different spatial scales. Experimental results show that the method achieves 75.63% mAP for wake detection, outperforming representative deep-learning baselines. The system simultaneously localizes ships and wakes on wide-area optical images, providing an effective tool for maritime surveillance, environmental protection, and ship navigation, and supporting subsequent ocean monitoring and analysis."
   },
   "report": "The paper introduces DHT-SWNet, an end-to-end single-stage target detection network built on a ResNet-101 backbone, designed to provide a technical basis for tracking illegal maritime operations and unauthorized vessel movements in protected or sovereign waters. By relying on complex deep learning architectures for spatial target detection, the methodology naturally aligns with the broader category of black-box spatial analysis. Consequently, while the research is primarily focused on advancing maritime surveillance capabilities, its foundational technical features intersect with ethical domains concerning the processing of geographic data and the tracking of targeted entities.\n\nThe auditor found no ethical risks actually instantiated by this paper's specific contribution; the identified pathways serve only as category-level disclosures for this class of technology. As a potential disclosure, the use of black-box spatial analysis plausibly promotes inadvertent inferential errors, a risk that conditionally emerges when complex multidimensional geographic variables are processed without transparent guardrails. If such inferential errors were to occur, they hold a moderate potential to subsequently trigger inequitable social outcomes, including equal rights violations. This secondary risk conditionally holds in the absence of ethical guides to provide checks and balances on data and methods. Because the paper's own method does not perform actions that trigger these harms, these risks are disclosed solely as theoretical associations with the broader technological class. \n\nThe provided text does not detail specific mitigations, as the paper's scope is strictly constrained to presenting the technical detection architecture. In the overall auditor's judgment, out of the two causal pathways extracted, zero are instantiated as actual findings against the research, while both function merely as moderate-confidence disclosures of potential category risk. Ultimately, the methodology does not concretely trigger any recognizable ethical harm in its current form, ensuring that the study avoids actively introducing the inequitable social outcomes associated with its general application domain.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (black-box spatial analysis:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When complex multidimensional geographic variables are processed without transparent guardrails.)\n- (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable social outcomes:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the absence of ethical guides to provide checks and balances on data and methods.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box spatial analysis\n  RiskMechanism: inadvertent inferential error\n  EthicalImpact: inequitable social outcomes",
