   "source": {
    "title": "Towards assessing the synthetic-to-measured adversarial vulnerability of SAR ATR",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2024.06.004",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2024.06.004",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2024",
    "abstract": "Recently, there has been increasing concern about the vulnerability of deep neural network (DNN)-based synthetic aperture radar (SAR) automatic target recognition (ATR) to adversarial attacks, where a DNN could be easily deceived by clean input with imperceptible but aggressive perturbations. This paper studies the synthetic-to-measured (S2M) transfer setting, where an attacker generates adversarial perturbation based solely on synthetic data and transfers it against victim models trained with measured data. Compared with the current measured-to-measured (M2M) transfer setting, our approach does not need direct access to the victim model or the measured SAR data. We also propose the transferability estimation attack (TEA) to uncover the adversarial risks in this more challenging and practical scenario. The TEA makes full use of the limited similarity between the synthetic and measured data pairs for blind estimation and optimization of S2M transferability, leading to feasible surrogate model enhancement without mastering the victim model and data. Comprehensive evaluations based on the publicly available synthetic and measured paired labeled experiment (SAMPLE) dataset demonstrate that the TEA outperforms state-of-the-art methods and can significantly enhance various attack algorithms in computer vision and remote sensing applications. Codes and data are available at https://github.com/scenarri/S2M-TEA."
   },
   "report": "The technical contribution of this paper centers on the generation of adversarial perturbations, specifically focusing on a synthetic-to-measured transfer setting where attackers generate perturbations based exclusively on synthetic data to transfer them against victim models trained on measured data. By actively creating and evaluating these attack mechanisms, the paper's technical framework directly touches upon the ethics of artificial intelligence security and reliability. The primary ethical touchpoint resides in the deliberate manipulation of system inputs to exploit vulnerabilities within target models. \n\nAs an instantiated finding, the auditor notes with strong confidence that the paper's use of adversarial perturbations directly promotes the misleading of machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions. This instantiated risk is firmly grounded in the paper's methodology and explicitly materializes under the condition of the inference stage of machine learning models. Beyond this direct finding, the audit discloses a broader, potential category risk: misleading machine learning models in this manner is moderately associated with downstream safety risks and potential physical harm in critical missions. However, this severe downstream consequence only applies under the condition of deployment in safety-critical geoscience and remote sensing tasks—such as sensitive defense or automated vehicle identification systems—and remains strictly a potential disclosure rather than a harm instantiated by this paper's contained experiments.\n\nThe extracted records do not detail any specific mitigations or defensive measures implemented by the authors to neutralize the vulnerabilities they evaluate. In the overall auditor's judgment, the paper presents exactly one strongly grounded, instantiated ethical risk concerning the intentional degradation of model accuracy, alongside one potential disclosure regarding hypothetical downstream safety impacts. Because the most severe physical and mission-critical harms remain uninstantiated and reliant on specific, high-stakes operational contexts, the paper's actual ethical footprint is strictly confined to demonstrating the technical unreliability of models under targeted adversarial attack.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (adversarial perturbations:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: inference stage of machine learning models)\n- (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: safety-critical geoscience and remote sensing tasks)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: adversarial perturbations\n  RiskMechanism: misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions",
