   "id": "010",
   "source": {
    "title": "Improving interpretability of deep active learning for flood inundation mapping through class ambiguity indices using multi-spectral satellite imagery",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2024.114213",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2024.114213",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2024",
    "abstract": "Flood inundation mapping is a critical task for responding to the increasing risk of flooding linked to global warming. Significant advancements of deep learning in recent years have triggered its extensive applications, including flood inundation mapping. To cope with the time-consuming and labor-intensive data labeling process in supervised learning, deep active learning strategies are one of the feasible approaches. However, there remains limited exploration into the interpretability of how deep active learning strategies operate, with a specific focus on flood inundation mapping in the field of remote sensing. In this study, we introduce a novel framework of Interpretable Deep Active Learning for Flood inundation Mapping (IDAL-FIM), specifically in terms of class ambiguity of multi-spectral satellite images. In the experiments, we utilize Sen1Floods11 dataset, and adopt U-Net with MC-dropout. In addition, we employ five acquisition functions, which are the random, K-means, BALD, entropy, and margin acquisition functions. Based on the experimental results, we demonstrate that two proposed class ambiguity indices are effective variables to interpret the deep active learning by establishing statistically significant correlation with the predictive uncertainty of the deep learning model at the tile level. Then, we illustrate the behaviors of deep active learning through visualizing two-dimensional density plots and providing interpretations regarding the operation of deep act"
   },
   "report": "The technical contribution of this paper focuses on deep learning for semantic segmentation, specifically employing a U-Net architecture with Monte Carlo (MC) dropout to provide pixel-level uncertainty estimation. This methodology touches upon significant ethical dimensions within the Earth observation imaging process, particularly where the speed and accuracy of outputs directly influence responses to flood risks and global warming. By evaluating model performance in this context, the framework engages with the critical necessity of ensuring dependable algorithmic predictions during safety-critical tasks.\n\nAssessing the causal risk reasoning, the auditor finds no ethical harms actively generated by the methodology. Instead, the paper's utilization of uncertainty quantification is identified as a moderately grounded, instantiated mitigation, plausibly acting to inhibit the unreliability of algorithmic predictions under the specific condition of high-risk remote sensing applications. Because this reliability is proactively managed, the downstream danger wherein such unreliability promotes systemic failures in disaster or safety monitoring—which inherently carries risks of physical harm—is addressed and explicitly not triggered by the paper's approach. Additionally, as a broader category disclosure, systems in this remote sensing domain often employ human-in-the-loop GeoAI to further inhibit unethical or inaccurate machine-generated maps by allowing cartographers to directly intervene in output quality and visual assessment. However, this human-intervention mechanism remains solely a potential dynamic associated with the broader field and is not actually instantiated by the automated methodology presented in this paper.\n\nThe explicitly present mitigation in this work is the model's algorithmic uncertainty quantification strategy. Overall, the auditor concludes that there are zero ethical risks actually instantiated by this paper's contribution. The findings consist of one moderately grounded instantiated mitigation, one neutralized (not triggered) risk concerning disaster monitoring, and one potential disclosure regarding expert human oversight. Ultimately, the paper is fundamentally structured to preempt unreliability in safety-critical Earth observation, successfully managing category-level vulnerabilities without introducing any new ethical hazards.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (uncertainty quantification:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systemic failure in disaster or safety monitoring:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>  (when: Earth observation imaging process)\n- (human-in-the-loop geoai:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (unethical or inaccurate machine-generated maps:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: By allowing cartographers to intervene in output quality and visual assessment)\n\nEntities by type:\n  RiskMechanism: unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks\n  EthicalImpact: systemic failure in disaster or safety monitoring, unethical or inaccurate machine-generated maps\n  Mitigation: uncertainty quantification, human-in-the-loop geoai",
