   "id": "013",
   "source": {
    "title": "Calibration and uncertainty quantification for deep learning-based drought detection",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2025.104563",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2025.104563",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Droughts are hydrometeorological extreme events influenced by highly intricate land–atmosphere feedback mechanisms and climate variability. Deep learning models have recently succeeded in detecting extreme climate events and promise to uncover and understand droughts further. There are two main challenges of reliability and trustworthiness limiting their applications: miscalibration and inherent uncertainty. However, they remain rarely explored because deep learning models are overparameterized and seldom tractable. To address this shortcoming, we introduce methodologies for model calibration and entropy-based uncertainty quantification for deep learning-based drought detection. The calibration algorithm can deal with calibration errors by reducing distributional shifts and alleviating overconfident predictions. The uncertainty framework, in turn, decomposes and quantifies the total uncertainty according to several components: data uncertainty, procedural variability, parametric variability, and latent variability. Thus, our method identifies uncertain predictions and supports robust evaluations, benefiting the credibility of the decision-making process. Empirical evidence of performance in a wide range of European drought events is given, justifying the effectiveness of our approach. The calibration methodology yields the lowest expected calibration error (0.31%) and the precision of the uncertainty-based decision-making is improved from 72.27% to 74.06% and 76.59%, based on"
   },
   "report": "This paper focuses on improving the reliability and trustworthiness of deep neural networks deployed in climate science and remote sensing, specifically addressing the technical challenges associated with the models' \"black-box\" nature. To achieve this, the authors introduce a framework for uncertainty quantification that decomposes and quantifies total uncertainty into distinct components, aiming to correct overconfident predictions. The research intersects with ethical considerations primarily through its application in high-risk remote sensing tasks and hazard-sensitive Earth observation imaging, where the outputs of predictive models directly influence critical decision-making processes. \n\nThe auditor found no ethical risk actually instantiated by this paper's contribution; the findings consist solely of category-level disclosures regarding the broader technological domain. At the category level, there is a strong potential that a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability can promote safety risks and physical harm, specifically under the condition of high-risk remote sensing applications. Furthermore, within the context of the Earth observation imaging process, there is a plausible but uninstantiated potential that the unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks could lead to systemic failures in disaster or safety monitoring, potentially resulting in economic loss. Notably, the standard risk pathway where the black-box nature of deep neural networks promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency is deliberately not triggered by this paper; instead, the authors' methodology is designed to actively neutralize this mechanism by quantifying the reasons behind model uncertainty. \n\nThe paper contains a well-grounded, strong mitigation strategy: the use of uncertainty quantification effectively inhibits the unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks, particularly under the condition of high-risk remote sensing applications. Overall, the auditor's judgment is highly favorable. Out of the four evaluated risk dynamics, zero risks are actually instantiated by the paper, three serve purely as potential disclosures representing broader category risks, and one risk pathway is explicitly neutralized. Because the paper actively works to resolve the transparency and reliability limitations of deep learning, it raises no actionable ethical findings against its own contributions.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (uncertainty quantification:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systemic failure in disaster or safety monitoring:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Earth observation imaging process)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: unreliability of algorithmic predictions in safety-critical tasks, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: systemic failure in disaster or safety monitoring, safety risks in critical missions\n  Mitigation: uncertainty quantification",
