   "id": "014",
   "source": {
    "title": "Spatiotemporal crime prediction and fairness-constrained spatial optimization with deep reinforcement learning for patrol region design",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2025.104973",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2025.104973",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Existing police resource allocation relies on the prediction of historical crime hotspots, which is difficult to balance the overall effectiveness and regional fairness, resulting in an imbalance in the allocation of resources and difficulty in adapting to dynamic security needs. Taking Los Angeles as the study area, this study first constructs an XGBoost regression prediction model to quantify the future crime risk of each area based on the crime location and time information in the historical crime data, and then introduces the minimum regional disparity (MRD) constraint on the basis of which the fairness indicator is integrated into the optimization framework of patrol region allocation. Meanwhile, this study innovatively introduces a deep reinforcement learning method to improve the model’s solution efficiency and adaptability under complex constraints by interacting with the environment through a policy network. The experimental results show that the MRD fairness model significantly improves resource allocation fairness. Compared with the maximum coverage model, the Gini coefficient and coefficient of variation decrease by 42.56 % and 57.59 %, respectively, and the Jain’s fairness index simultaneously increases by 94.33 %. Regarding patrol region configuration, the proposed method decreases resource redundancy by 66.62 % and increases the spatial balance of facility distribution by 7.5 %, thereby effectively improving resource utilization and spatial layout rationality. "
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a deep reinforcement learning methodology to solve large-scale combinatorial site-selection problems, utilizing an encoder-decoder policy network equipped with multi-head attention and a gated recurrent unit (GRU). By casting the optimization challenge as a Markov Decision Process, the authors train their model via policy gradients to generate deployment sequences. The methodology intersects with ethical considerations through two specific technical features that act as risk triggers. First, the framework relies on precise geo-referencing, utilizing input records that contain exact date-time stamps, geographic coordinates, crime categories, and textual descriptions. Second, the fundamental architecture introduces the inherent complexity of deep neural networks into spatial decision-making. \n\nBased on these technical features, the auditor identifies two actually instantiated ethical risks within the paper’s methodology. First, the explicit use of high-resolution geo-referencing—specifically tying spatial coordinates and timestamps to crime data—plausibly promotes downstream privacy violations. Second, the reliance on an advanced deep reinforcement learning pipeline introduces the black-box nature of deep neural networks to the task. This opacity plausibly promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability regarding how the model generates its spatial deployment decisions. Both of these risks are designated as instantiated findings rather than mere theoretical disclosures, as the paper directly performs the triggering actions. They are assessed with moderate confidence, meaning the causal links to privacy harm and algorithmic opacity are plausible and structurally grounded in the paper's text, though qualified by how the system might eventually be deployed. There are no additional potential or uninstantiated category risks identified in this analysis.\n\nA review of the extracted claims reveals no technical mitigations or neutralizing features presented within the paper to address these issues. The overall auditor's judgment is that the methodology instantiates exactly two ethical risks and contains zero merely disclosed category risks. Because both the privacy vulnerabilities tied to the precise geo-referencing and the lack of transparency stemming from the black-box neural network are assessed as plausible but moderately qualified findings, they represent genuine structural concerns. Without corresponding safeguards to protect spatial privacy or mechanisms to interpret the opaque reinforcement learning outputs, the paper leaves these instantiated vulnerabilities unresolved within its technical contribution.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (geo-referencing:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: geo-referencing, black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: privacy violation",
