     "content": "explicit predictive modeling called XGBoost with SHAP to investigate truck crashes; the XAI showed a strong  correlation of crashes to the density of road usage and the adjacency to seaports. Li  (2022) compared XGBoost to  a geographically weighted regression to predict the geographic distribution of ride-  hailing service demand. Li used  SHAP to examine combinations of input variables like average trip distance and census tract coordinates. Simini  et al. (2021) employed SHAP to explain how different geographic input features impacted the output of their com - muting model. The three articles highlight the effectiveness of SHAP in finding influential input variables. LIME  was used by Amiri et al. (2021) and Parmar et al. (2021). LIME approximates the predictions of the black box model  using a local interpretable model, such as a linear regression, with a specific input variable(s). Parmar et al. (2021)  explained how land use patterns could predict parking duration. Amiri et al.  (2021) demonstrated how XAI could  be used to retune the model. They used LIME for hyperparameter tuning to increase the prediction accuracy of  household transportation energy consumption. Although they considered geographic issues, their explanation  approaches did not account for geographic structures like topology. This represents a significant challenge to  integrating XAI and GeoAI, which we explore in Section 4.2 . Soares et al. (2019) argued that simpler rule-  based approaches could offer better human interpretation,  especially when addressing the increasing complexity of classification optimization afforded by DNN. Soares  et al. (2019) first used a CNN to extract features of autonomous vehicles. They then developed a multi-  layer  neuro- fuzzy modeling method to extract large numbers of conditional (if … then) statements as rules for autono- mous vehicles in hazardous conditions. There could be an inverse relationship of XAI to GeoAI, where we should  explore simpler"
