   "id": "016",
   "source": {
    "title": "User and data-centric artificial intelligence for mapping and benchmarking urban deprivation for a global sample of cities",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2026.115272",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2026.115272",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Rapid urbanization across many regions worldwide has significantly contributed to the growth of deprived urban areas (DUAs), often called slums or informal settlements. The lack of reliable geospatial information on their location and extent in many cities continues to hinder efforts aimed at improving living conditions. This study addresses this critical information gap by exploring a User- and Data-centric Artificial Intelligence (AI) approach for accurately mapping these areas to support Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) Indicator 11.1.1. In collaboration with local communities, governments, and international stakeholders, we co-designed an AI-driven strategy leveraging open Earth Observation (EO) and geospatial data acrosseight cities worldwide. Instead of relying solely on algorithmic precision, our method prioritizes local knowledge, iterative validation, and adaptive data collection. To achieve this, we developed a tailored multi-branch encoder-decoder convolutional neural network capable of integrating multi-modal data sources. Our approach incorporates an agile and iterativemodel refinement process, ensuring continuous feedback loops between AI design, data collection, and validation. Recognizing the importance of stakeholder engagement, we developed the IDEAtlas collaborative data collection platform - https://portal.ideatlas.eu/ - to enhance data quality and inclusivity. The resulting dataset (IDEABench) is publicly available at https://doi.org/10.17026/PT/X4NJII "
   },
   "report": "This paper utilizes AI technology and geo-referencing to process remote sensing data, actively addressing training data quality to improve spatial mapping precision. The technical framework inherently intersects with several sensitive ethical domains, including community privacy concerns surrounding the publication of geo-referenced maps, the risk of algorithmic bias in system design, and the reliability of system outputs. Because the resulting maps are visualized by stakeholders to support improvements in public policies and socioeconomic interventions, the paper’s underlying technical methodology touches upon the profound societal implications of data accuracy, responsible AI deployment, and human-centric system design.\n\nIn evaluating the causal risk pathways, the auditor identifies one moderately grounded, instantiated finding against the paper: the utilization of varying training data quality plausibly promotes system failures and inaccurate results. The paper explicitly encounters this technical reality, noting that its reference data contained \"noisy\" or outdated labels that required iterative refinement to sufficiently increase mapping precision. Stemming from this technical finding is a moderate potential disclosure that system failures and inaccurate results can promote serious economic consequences. However, this remains strictly a category-level disclosure; the economic risk is contingent upon the inaccuracies occurring in critical business areas such as finance, healthcare, or security, and is therefore not actually instantiated or triggered by this paper's specific contributions to public policy visualization. \n\nDespite the instantiated technical challenge regarding data accuracy, the paper proactively neutralizes its most severe ethical risks through deliberate mitigations. A strongly grounded risk of bias—which typically arises when AI technology development lacks integration with the humanities—is explicitly avoided because the researchers prioritize local knowledge, iterative validation, and adaptive data collection over strict algorithmic precision. By refusing to overrely on AI results without local expertise, the authors also successfully avert a strongly grounded risk that systemic bias could lead to the misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data. Furthermore, a plausible risk of privacy violations stemming from geo-referencing is fully neutralized, as the paper intentionally down-samples publicly available maps to a 100-meter resolution to protect community privacy. Overall, the auditor concludes that the paper instantiates only a single, mathematically manageable technical risk regarding training data noise, while successfully resolving its primary ethical risks regarding privacy and bias.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (geo-referencing:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>\n- (ai technology:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: Development lacking integration with the humanities)\n- (bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: Overreliance on AI results without local expertise)\n- (training data quality:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (system failures and inaccurate results:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (system failures and inaccurate results:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (serious economic consequences:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When occurring in critical business areas such as finance, healthcare, or security.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: geo-referencing, ai technology, training data quality\n  RiskMechanism: bias, system failures and inaccurate results\n  EthicalImpact: privacy violation, misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data, serious economic consequences",
