   "id": "022",
   "source": {
    "title": "Exploration of OpenStreetMap missing built-up areas using twitter hierarchical clustering and deep learning in Mozambique",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2020.05.007",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2020.05.007",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2020",
    "abstract": "Accurate and detailed geographical information digitizing human activity patterns plays an essential role in response to natural disasters. Volunteered geographical information, in particular OpenStreetMap (OSM), shows great potential in providing the knowledge of human settlements to support humanitarian aid, while the availability and quality of OSM remains a major concern. The majority of existing works in assessing OSM data quality focus on either extrinsic or intrinsic analysis, which is insufficient to fulfill the humanitarian mapping scenario to a certain degree. This paper aims to explore OSM missing built-up areas from an integrative perspective of social sensing and remote sensing. First, applying hierarchical DBSCAN clustering algorithm, the clusters of geo-tagged tweets are generated as proxies of human active regions. Then a deep learning based model fine-tuned on existing OSM data is proposed to further map the missing built-up areas. Hit by Cyclone Idai and Kenneth in 2019, the Republic of Mozambique is selected as the study area to evaluate the proposed method at a national scale. As a result, 13 OSM missing built-up areas are identified and mapped with an over 90% overall accuracy, being competitive compared to state-of-the-art products, which confirms the effectiveness of the proposed method."
   },
   "report": "The technical scope of this paper centers on AI-driven building detection and informal settlement mapping from remote sensing imagery, alongside the use of data integration and modeling to identify missing built-up areas in crowdsourced datasets like OpenStreetMap. Ethically, the technical features utilized in this study—specifically the classification of remote sensing data, informal settlement mapping, and the handling of social and crowdsourced datasets—intersect with sensitive downstream applications such as humanitarian aid, emergency service routing, and urban planning. By aiming to ensure human habitations in sparsely populated or informal areas are mapped to reduce vulnerability, the research operates within a domain historically prone to geographic bias and socioeconomic impacts, prompting an evaluation of the broader methodological risks associated with this domain.\n\nThe auditor found no ethical risks actually instantiated by this paper's contribution; the findings represent disclosures of category-level risks that the applied techniques can raise in general, rather than harms triggered by the authors. Within this category-level disclosure, AI-driven building detection and classification plausibly promote the misclassification of heterogeneous roof types if the training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure. This misclassification could subsequently lead to discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid, conditional upon roof typology being used as a proxy for socioeconomic status. Furthermore, informal settlement mapping carries a plausible potential to elevate vulnerable population risk—and eventually lead to forced displacement and economic loss—in contexts where authorities misuse high-resolution mapping for enforcement or the removal of informal dwellings rather than for developmental support. Additionally, reliance on biased social and crowdsourced datasets holds the potential to promote systematic discrimination when applied to urban planning applications. \n\nRegarding mitigations, the paper presents a strongly grounded approach to resolving representational harms through its primary methodology. The use of data integration and modeling strongly inhibits sampling bias toward dominant cultures, operating effectively when used to correct bias and locate missing structures in crowdsourced datasets by combining multiple data sources. Ultimately, the auditor judges that zero ethical risks are instantiated by this paper, with all six causal pathways functioning merely as contextual disclosures (five moderate-confidence risk disclosures and one strong-confidence mitigation). The paper remains ethically silent regarding direct harms, securely navigating its technical contributions without materializing the systemic vulnerabilities broadly associated with geospatial artificial intelligence.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (data integration and modeling:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (sampling bias toward dominant cultures:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When used to correct bias in crowdsourced or VGI datasets by combining multiple data sources.)\n- (ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types)\n- (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When roof typology is used as a proxy for socio-economic status)\n- (biased social and crowdsourced datasets:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (systematic discrimination:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When used in urban planning applications)\n- (informal settlement mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (vulnerable population risk:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: If authorities use high-resolution mapping for enforcement rather than developmental support.)\n- (vulnerable population risk:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (forced displacement:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In contexts where data is used to facilitate the removal of informal dwellings.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data, biased social and crowdsourced datasets, informal settlement mapping\n  RiskMechanism: sampling bias toward dominant cultures, misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, vulnerable population risk\n  EthicalImpact: discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid, systematic discrimination, forced displacement\n  Mitigation: data integration and modeling",
