   "source": {
    "title": "Physically-aware deep learning for reconstructing gap-free sea surface temperature in the South China Sea",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.04.016",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.04.016",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Missing data caused by cloud cover, sensor limitations, and orbital gaps remain a fundamental challenge for many satellite-derived geophysical products, limiting their utility in environmental monitoring and climate research. To address this issue, we propose a physically informed deep learning framework, the Peripheral Feature-assisted Fourier-transform Convolutional Bidirectional LSTM (PFTCBiLSTM), for reconstructing spatiotemporally coherent fields from incomplete remote sensing imagery. The model combines Fourier-domain convolutional layers, which capture spatial frequency characteristics, with bidirectional recurrent units that represent nonlinear temporal dependencies, while auxiliary geophysical drivers provide physical context for air–sea interactions. Using geostationary satellite observations over the South China Sea as a test case, PFTCBiLSTM demonstrated substantial improvements over advanced baseline models. The final configuration reduced the mean absolute error (MAE) from 0.33 °C for FTC-LSTM to 0.21 °C and the root mean square error (RMSE) from 0.51 °C to 0.35 °C, while increasing the structural similarity index (SSIM) to 0.98 and maintaining R2 = 0.98. Independent validation against NOAA iQuam in situ observations confirmed robust performance across both deep-basin and coastal regimes, particularly in cloud-prone and dynamically complex regions. Sensitivity experiments, Shapley Additive Explanations (SHAP), and adversarial robustness tests using projected gra"
   },
   "report": "The audited paper presents a physically informed deep learning framework designed to reconstruct spatiotemporally coherent fields from incomplete remote sensing imagery. Technically, the method enhances the detection of marine heatwaves to provide more reliable data for regional climate monitoring and emergency response for maritime communities. The primary ethical touchpoints for this work reside in its application to such critical, high-stakes domains, where the foundational reliance on deep neural networks typically intersects with concerns over model interpretability. \n\nThe auditor found no ethical risks actually instantiated by this paper's contribution. The identified concerns serve solely as category-level disclosures relevant to the broader field of deep learning in remote sensing. Specifically, there is a moderately grounded potential disclosure that a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability could promote safety risks in critical missions. However, this potential impact is contingent upon the condition that the system is deployed in high-risk remote sensing applications, such as direct emergency response. Importantly, the paper actively avoids triggering this pathway; it neutralizes the initiating technical vulnerability—the traditional black-box nature of deep neural networks—by embedding physical principles directly into its deep learning framework. \n\nIn terms of mitigations and overall judgment, the paper's explicit use of a physically informed architecture acts as an intrinsic safeguard against the opacity typically found in unconstrained neural networks. Because this design choice addresses the root mechanism of algorithmic transparency, the auditor concludes that zero risks are instantiated as actual audit findings. The evaluation yields only a single potential disclosure regarding downstream safety in critical maritime missions, alongside a notable confirmation that the black-box risk pathway is deliberately not triggered. Overall, the paper effectively balances its technical contributions to climate monitoring with structural mitigations that preempt the ethical hazards of unexplainable artificial intelligence.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions",
