   "id": "024",
   "source": {
    "title": "Nonlinear effects of urban multidimensional characteristics on daytime and nighttime land surface temperature in highly urbanized regions: A case study in Beijing, China",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2024.104067",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2024.104067",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2024",
    "abstract": "It is crucial to clarify the nonlinear effects of urban multidimensional characteristics on land surface temperature (LST). However, the combined consideration of the urban green space (UGS), water bodies, buildings, and socio-economic factors is limited. And the diurnal differences in their thermal effects have been less considered. In this study, central Beijing was taken as study area. Local climate zones (LCZ) were firstly applied to reveal spatiotemporal heterogeneity of LST. Then, the interpretable machine learning methods were utilized to quantitatively reveal nonlinear thermal effects of urban multidimensional characteristics, i.e., the UGS, water bodies, and building landscape features, and socio-economic features. The results indicated that built type LCZs have a higher average LST compared to natural type LCZs. And the LST of built type LCZs is simultaneously influenced by buildings’ density and height characteristics. Daytime LST is mainly affected by the landscape proportions of UGS, buildings, and trees, while nighttime LST is more influenced by socio-economic and building characteristics. The thermal effects of key factors exhibit nonlinear characteristics. Whether during the day or night, the impact of building coverage on LST is greater than that of building height, consistently exhibiting a warming effect. While, the building height and water body edge density factors both exhibited a reversal trend in their thermal impact between day and night. Our study al"
   },
   "report": "This paper employs interpretable machine learning methods to quantitatively reveal the nonlinear thermal effects of multidimensional urban characteristics, including urban green spaces, water bodies, building landscapes, and socio-economic features. The technical objective involves providing specific thresholds for building density and height to guide the development of climate-resilient cities and sustainable urban forms. Ethically, the methodology touches upon the vital intersection of algorithmic explainability and urban planning, where data-driven outputs directly inform policies that shape the built environment. Because the framework generates guidelines intended to influence real-world urban layouts, it operates in a sensitive domain where algorithmic outputs must remain accountable to the communities they affect.\n\nIn evaluating the causal risk reasoning, the auditor notes that the methodological choices of the study proactively prevent potential harms. There is strong, instantiated evidence that the paper's explicit use of transparency—achieved through its interpretable machine learning approach—directly inhibits the risk mechanism of model opacity and lack of interpretability, specifically under the condition of urban decision-making processes. Because this opacity is constrained, downstream harms are averted. Specifically, there is a moderately plausible category-level dynamic where model opacity can promote spatial justice and accountability violations, notably under the condition that the model impacts citizens' lives through planning decisions. However, because the authors utilized an interpretable framework, this downstream risk is strictly not triggered by the paper; the threat to equal rights is neutralized before it can materialize. \n\nUltimately, the auditor found no ethical risks actually instantiated by this paper's contribution. Out of the evaluated dynamics, the single instantiated finding represents a strongly grounded mitigation rather than a hazard, while the sole potential risk is effectively bypassed and not triggered. By embedding transparency directly into its analytical pipeline, the paper successfully addresses the inherent opacity often found in spatial modeling. The overall judgment is that the study acts responsibly within its scope, demonstrating how interpretable methodologies can prevent accountability violations in urban planning and ensure that data-driven sustainability thresholds remain both accessible and just.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (transparency:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (model opacity and lack of interpretability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: Urban decision-making processes)\n- (model opacity and lack of interpretability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (spatial justice and accountability violations:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>  (when: When impacting citizens' lives through planning decisions)\n\nEntities by type:\n  RiskMechanism: model opacity and lack of interpretability\n  EthicalImpact: spatial justice and accountability violations\n  Mitigation: transparency",
