   "id": "025",
   "source": {
    "title": "Multi-spatial urban function modeling: A multi-modal deep network approach for transfer and multi-task learning",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2025.104397",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2025.104397",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Understanding dynamics of urban land-use is crucial for comprehending urban spaces and evaluating planning strategies. A range of data-driven models based on the representation learning of multiple data sources have focused on extracting spatially explicit characteristics at the feature level for urban function inference. However, they commonly pay no attention to the systematic relationships between urban land-use and transportation as the core components of urban systems. Consequently, while performing relatively well in urban land-use recognition, these models cannot transfer across various urban tasks and have almost no generalizability in integrated urban modeling. Guided by the theory of integrated land-use and transport modeling, this study proposes a multi-modal deep learning model to leverage the systematic relationships between urban components. First, spaces of urban places, urban forms, urban flows, and urban locations are conceptualized from the interactions between land use and transportation systems and represented by multi-source heterogeneous spatial features. Second, to account for both direct and indirect interactions in these spaces, a Deep &amp; Wide network is introduced to fuse different modalities of spatial features. Using Shenzhen city as a testbed, extensive experimental results show that our approach improves accuracy by 13.3% compared to state-of-the-art models. We further validate the superior generalizability of our approach across various urban"
   },
   "report": "This paper introduces technical workflows involving deep learning models for population mapping and GeoAI foundation models—specifically a Vision Transformer-based SatMAE—for feature extraction from multi-scale imagery. Additionally, the study employs mobile location data mapping, utilizing over seven million mobile phone signaling records to capture urban mobility, residential and working population densities, and human interaction with urban infrastructure. These technical features inherently intersect with sensitive ethical domains because they process granular traces of human mobility and attempt to quantify socio-spatial dynamics at scale.\n\nBecause the paper focuses on methodology rather than deploying an operational system, the auditor notes several potential, category-level disclosures, but finds no risks actively triggered by the text. First, the use of mobile location data mapping moderately associates with the risk of individual re-identification and subsequent location privacy violations, strictly conditioned on scenarios where de-identification is insufficient, or anonymous datasets are publicly shared, exposing home and workspace trajectories. Similarly, employing GeoAI foundation models carries a moderate, conditional risk of disclosing sensitive geospatial data during pre-training and fine-tuning phases. Finally, there is a strong theoretical disclosure that deep learning models for population mapping can promote population estimation bias, particularly under conditions of spatial heterogeneity and varying neighborhood sizes. This bias moderately risks inequitable resource and service distribution, but only if the models are subsequently used to facilitate actual resource allocation or disaster preparedness.\n\nThe provided text does not detail explicit mitigations for these broader systemic vulnerabilities. Overall, the auditor concludes that there are zero instantiated ethical risks triggered by this paper's specific contributions. All identified elements function exclusively as potential disclosures regarding the broader class of urban predictive modeling and mobile data analysis. While the underlying mechanisms for location privacy violations and spatial inequities are moderately to strongly recognized in the field, this paper itself does not cross the threshold into materializing these harms, leaving the study effectively ethics-silent regarding direct negative impacts.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (mobile location data mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (individual re-identification:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n- (individual re-identification:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (location privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When de-identification is insufficient to protect sensitive location traces | When anonymous datasets are publicly shared without sufficient protection)\n- (deep learning models for population mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Under conditions of spatial heterogeneity and varying neighborhood sizes)\n- (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable resource and service distribution:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When models are used to facilitate resource allocation and disaster preparedness)\n- (geoai foundation models:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (disclosure of sensitive geospatial data:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: During pre-training and fine-tuning stages with geospatial data)\n- (disclosure of sensitive geospatial data:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (location privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: non-public data associated with industry or national security | When exposing home locations, workspaces, and daily trajectories)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: mobile location data mapping, deep learning models for population mapping, geoai foundation models\n  RiskMechanism: individual re-identification, population estimation bias, disclosure of sensitive geospatial data\n  EthicalImpact: location privacy violation, inequitable resource and service distribution",
