   "id": "026",
   "source": {
    "title": "Global Streetscapes — A comprehensive dataset of 10 million street-level images across 688 cities for urban science and analytics",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2024.06.023",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2024.06.023",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2024",
    "abstract": "Street view imagery (SVI) is instrumental for sensing urban environments, benefitting numerous domains such as urban morphology, health, greenery, and accessibility. Billions of images worldwide have been made available by commercial services such as Google Street View and crowdsourcing services such as Mapillary and KartaView where anyone from anywhere can upload imagery while moving. However, while the data tend to be plentiful, have high coverage and quality, and are used to derive rich insights, they remain simple and limited in metadata as characteristics such as weather, quality, and lighting conditions remain unknown, making it difficult to evaluate the suitability of the images for specific analyses. We introduce Global Streetscapes — a dataset of 10 million crowdsourced and free-to-use SVIs sampled from 688 cities across 210 countries and territories, enriched with more than 300 camera, geographical, temporal, contextual, semantic, and perceptual attributes. The cities included are well balanced and diverse, and are home to about 10% of the world’s population. Deep learning models are trained on a subset of manually labelled images for eight visual-contextual attributes pertaining to the usability of SVI — panoramic status, lighting condition, view direction, weather, platform, quality, presence of glare and reflections, achieving accuracy ranging from 68.3% to 99.9%, and used to automatically label the entire dataset. Thanks to its scale and pre-computed standard se"
   },
   "report": "This paper introduces \"Global Streetscapes,\" a large-scale dataset comprising 10 million crowdsourced Street View Images (SVIs) sampled from 688 cities globally. Technically, the authors integrate and model data by harmonizing multiple geospatial sources, specifically Mapillary and KartaView, to create an enriched dataset. Furthermore, the paper employs automated deep learning models trained on manually labelled subsets to predict visual-contextual attributes—such as lighting conditions, weather, and panoramic status—achieving high accuracy to label the entire dataset automatically. The ethical triggers in this work lie primarily at the intersection of integrating crowdsourced multi-source geodata and utilizing opaque, automated machine learning models for vast geospatial classification. \n\nRegarding causal risk reasoning, the auditor identifies only one instantiated risk pathway in this paper. With moderate confidence, the auditor finds that the paper’s use of deep learning for automatic dataset labeling introduces a black-box technical feature that promotes model opacity and a lack of interpretability, a risk standardly conditional upon general urban geospatial AI implementations. Beyond this instantiated finding, the auditor notes several potential category-level disclosures that are not triggered by the paper’s direct actions. With strong confidence, the technique of mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and AI is known to promote the unintentional disclosure of sensitive information when combining seemingly unrelated datasets creates new information products. Plausibly, this unintentional disclosure can subsequently promote group privacy violations if detailed demographic clusters become accessible to the public (moderate confidence). Additionally, the auditor discloses with moderate confidence that model opacity could theoretically promote spatial justice and accountability violations when it directly impacts citizens' lives through planning decisions, and that algorithmic bias can promote marginalization and exclusion if the underlying data excludes vulnerable groups like children, older adults, homeless individuals, or people with disabilities. Because the paper does not engage in planning decisions or trigger these exclusions, these remain mere disclosures.\n\nFortunately, the paper actively deploys methodological mitigations against historical data inequities. The auditor finds with moderate confidence that the authors’ data integration and modeling approach practically inhibits algorithmic bias; this instantiated mitigation is achieved by correcting bias in volunteered geographic information (VGI) datasets through the combination of multiple data sources to ensure overlapping, complementary coverage. Overall, out of six identified ethical pathways, only two are actually instantiated by the paper: one moderate-confidence risk regarding model opacity and one moderate-confidence mitigation that actively reduces spatial bias. The remaining four pathways represent potential disclosures of broader category risks—such as privacy violations and spatial justice harms—that the paper does not trigger. Consequently, the paper’s instantiated ethical risks are limited and offset by its proactive efforts to harmonize diverse sources and improve equitable geographic representation.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (data integration and modeling:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When used to correct bias in crowdsourced or VGI datasets by combining multiple data sources.)\n- (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (marginalization and exclusion:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When data excludes children, older adults, homeless individuals, or people with disabilities.)\n- (mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and ai:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (unintentional disclosure of sensitive information:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When combining seemingly unrelated datasets creates new information products)\n- (unintentional disclosure of sensitive information:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (group privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: If detailed demographic clusters become accessible to the public)\n- (black-box nature:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (model opacity and lack of interpretability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: General urban geospatial AI implementation)\n- (model opacity and lack of interpretability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (spatial justice and accountability violations:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When impacting citizens' lives through planning decisions)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and ai, black-box nature\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic bias, unintentional disclosure of sensitive information, model opacity and lack of interpretability\n  EthicalImpact: marginalization and exclusion, group privacy violation, spatial justice and accountability violations\n  Mitigation: data integration and modeling",
