   "source": {
    "title": "UAV in the advent of the twenties: Where we stand and what is next",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2021.12.006",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2021.12.006",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2022",
    "abstract": "The use of Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAVs) has surged in the last two decades, making them popular instruments for a wide range of applications, and leading to a remarkable number of scientific contributions in geoscience, remote sensing and engineering. However, the development of best practices for high quality of UAV mapping are often overlooked representing a drawback for their wider adoption. UAV solutions then require an inter-disciplinary research, integrating different expertise and combining several hardware and software components on the same platform. Despite the high number of peer-reviewed papers on UAVs, little attention has been given to the interaction between research topics from different domains (such as robotics and computer vision) that impact the use of UAV in remote sensing. The aim of this paper is to (i) review best practices for the use of UAVs for remote sensing and mapping applications and (ii) report on current trends - including adjacent domains - for UAV use and discuss their future impact in photogrammetry and remote sensing. Hardware developments, navigation and acquisition strategies, and emerging solutions for data processing in innovative applications are considered in this analysis. As the number and the heterogeneity of debated topics are large, the paper is organized according to very specific questions considered most relevant by the authors."
   },
   "report": "This paper applies artificial intelligence techniques to remote sensing data, focusing on GeoAI for disaster management and AI-driven building detection and classification. Technically, the method touches on the automated delineation of visible cadastral boundaries within informal or vulnerable settlements, alongside real-time semantic analysis to detect structural building damage after earthquakes in support of search-and-rescue operations. Ethically, these application areas intersect with systemic concerns regarding the accurate representation and categorization of human infrastructure across diverse geographic environments.\n\nThe auditor found no ethical risk actually instantiated by this paper's contribution. The identified ethical dynamics function exclusively as potential disclosures regarding the broader class of techniques to which this paper’s methods belong, rather than direct findings against its specific methodology. First, there is a moderately confident disclosure that AI-driven building detection can lead to the misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, provided the condition is met where training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types. If this roof typology is subsequently used as a proxy for socio-economic status, it could plausibly foster resource allocation inequalities and equal rights violations. Second, the use of GeoAI for disaster management is associated with a general risk of representation bias, which can cause false negatives for building damage specifically in rural or impoverished regions. Under those geographic conditions, such algorithmic blind spots might lead to the denial of critical resources to marginalized populations, posing a plausible risk of physical harm. \n\nNo specific mitigations are extracted from the paper. In the overall auditor's judgment, the paper presents zero instantiated ethical findings against its actual contributions, alongside four potential risk disclosures reflecting broader category-level hazards. Because none of these causal risk chains are triggered by the paper’s direct technical actions, the text is fundamentally out of scope for generating direct harm and may be considered ethics-silent on self-instantiated risks. The noted disclosures serve only to contextualize the systemic hazards inherent to remote sensing in disaster response and settlement monitoring, ensuring categorical awareness without manufacturing a harm narrative against the research itself.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types)\n- (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When roof typology is used as a proxy for socio-economic status)\n- (GeoAI for disaster management:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (representation bias false negatives for buildings in rural or poor areas:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Rural or impoverished regions)\n- (representation bias false negatives for buildings in rural or poor areas:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (denial of resources to marginalized populations:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Rural or impoverished regions)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data, GeoAI for disaster management\n  RiskMechanism: misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, representation bias false negatives for buildings in rural or poor areas\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, denial of resources to marginalized populations",
