   "id": "029",
   "source": {
    "title": "UPDExplainer: An interpretable transformer-based framework for urban physical disorder detection using street view imagery",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2023.08.017",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2023.08.017",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Urban Physical Disorder (UPD), such as old or abandoned buildings, broken sidewalks, litter, and graffiti, has a negative impact on residents’ quality of life. They can also increase crime rates, cause social disorder, and pose a public health risk. Currently, there is a lack of efficient and reliable methods for detecting and understanding UPD. To bridge this gap, we propose UPDExplainer, an interpretable transformer-based framework for UPD detection. We first develop a UPD detection model based on the Swin Transformer architecture, which leverages readily accessible street view images to learn discriminative representations. To provide clear and comprehensible evidence and analysis, we subsequently introduce a UPD factor identification and ranking module that combines visual explanation maps with semantic segmentation maps. This novel integrated approach enables us to identify the exact objects within street view images that are responsible for physical disorders and gain insight into the underlying causes. Experimental results on the re-annotated Place Pulse 2.0 dataset demonstrate promising detection performance of the proposed method, surpassing the state-of-the-art with an increase of 6.54% in Accuracy and 7.05% in F1 score. For a comprehensive evaluation of the method’s ranking performance, we provide both quantitative and qualitative results, highlighting the model’s precise identification of one, two, three, and four UPD factors, respectively. We also present a case "
   },
   "report": "This paper focuses on machine learning-based mapping to identify physical disorders within urban environments, utilizing a re-annotated version of the Place Pulse dataset containing historical street view images. The technical approach intersects with ethical considerations because it involves the categorization of \"disordered neighborhoods,\" which frequently overlap with underserved or vulnerable communities. Additionally, the research touches upon visualization techniques designed to isolate the exact spatial objects within street view imagery that contribute to these classifications, aiming to provide insight into the underlying causes of localized urban conditions.\n\nThe auditor found no ethical risk actually instantiated by this paper's contribution; the identified pathways are strictly potential disclosures reflecting category-level risks rather than direct harms caused by this work. Within this methodological class, there is a moderately grounded potential disclosure that training data errors in machine learning-based mapping could promote the misrepresentation of urban areas, a risk that is explicitly conditional upon the mapping of Deprived Urban Areas (DUAs). Consequently, there is a related moderate, theoretical disclosure that such misrepresentation could promote the social stigmatization of community members—functioning as an equal rights violation—given the research context of identifying underserved populations. However, the paper itself does not perform the actions required to trigger these downstream impacts, and they remain purely categorical warnings.\n\nRegarding risk management, this domain of research is associated with a strongly grounded potential mitigation: utilizing a visualization-based mitigation strategy. When conditionally applied during the data audit stage to reveal clusters, this approach strongly inhibits the masking of subpopulation conditions by identifying the exact objects responsible for physical disorder classifications. Ultimately, the auditor’s judgment is that zero ethical risks are actually instantiated by the paper, while three relationships serve merely as contextual, category-level disclosures. Because the methodology does not trigger the identified risk mechanisms, the paper remains structurally safe and does not manufacture a direct harm narrative.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (training data errors in ml-based mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misrepresentation of urban areas:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Mapping of Deprived Urban Areas (DUAs))\n- (misrepresentation of urban areas:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (social stigmatization of community members:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n- (Visualization-based mitigation:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (masking of subpopulation conditions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Used during the data audit stage to reveal clusters)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: training data errors in ml-based mapping\n  RiskMechanism: misrepresentation of urban areas, masking of subpopulation conditions\n  EthicalImpact: social stigmatization of community members\n  Mitigation: Visualization-based mitigation",
