   "id": "030",
   "source": {
    "title": "GeoSight v2: strengthening disaster impact assessment with coordinate referencing, inpainting, and similarity models",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.03.030",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2026.03.030",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Post-disaster imagery collected by communities and field teams provides critical visual evidence for assessing damage and guiding emergency responses. However, the geocoordinates embedded in these images often capture the camera’s location rather than the position of the depicted building, introducing spatial misalignment that reduces mapping accuracy and weakens machine learning–based decision support. To address this challenge, we present an enhanced version of GeoSight, a geolocation refinement framework that integrates three key components: (i) coordinate referencing to constrain candidate search areas, (ii) building detection with inpainting to isolate structures and remove unrelated objects such as vehicles and debris, and (iii) perceptual similarity analysis using DreamSim to match query images against a georeferenced database. Using NOAA’s 2023 Norman, Oklahoma tornado building-damage imagery, the enhanced framework improves retrieval accuracy from 53% to 67% (Top-1) and 77% to 84% (Top-3), while reducing average geolocation errors by 26.1 m, with maximum corrections up to 46.5 m. By combining coordinate data, object-level preprocessing, and perceptual similarity, this framework provides a scalable and generalizable approach for refining the geolocation of community-driven disaster imagery, enabling more accurate and timely damage mapping for disaster response and recovery."
   },
   "report": "The technical contribution of this work centers on an enhanced version of the GeoSight geolocation refinement framework. To achieve its results, the methodology integrates coordinate referencing to constrain candidate search areas, building detection with inpainting to isolate architectural structures while removing unrelated objects like vehicles, and perceptual similarity analysis to match query images against a georeferenced database. By actively utilizing fine-grained geo-referencing techniques to pinpoint specific locations and precisely match imagery to real-world coordinates, the system's technical pipeline directly establishes the ethical touchpoint for this audit. \n\nAs an instantiated audit finding, the auditor strongly concludes that the paper's deployment of geo-referencing actively promotes risks of privacy violation. Because the framework specifically refines geolocation by constraining geographic search areas and matching query images to a mapped database, it provides the exact technical mechanisms that can expose sensitive locations or inadvertently trace spatial whereabouts. There are no merely potential category risks to disclose for this paper; rather, the privacy violation risk is directly triggered and instantiated by the paper's core methodological focus on precise location extraction and georeferenced matching.\n\nThe provided text does not introduce any mitigations or safeguards to address or neutralize this resulting privacy vulnerability. In the overall judgment of the auditor, the paper instantiates exactly one ethical risk, while disclosing zero risks as merely potential or category-level. This single finding regarding privacy violation is highly grounded in the authors' explicit description of their geolocation refinement pipeline, meaning the technical contribution carries an unmitigated, directly instantiated ethical risk.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (geo-referencing:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: geo-referencing\n  EthicalImpact: privacy violation",
