     "source": "chen2026_ethical_spatial_analysis.pdf",
     "content": "al. 2010; Shi 2010), parameter choice is a critical source of  bias. As Fig. 2 (c) illustrates, an overly large bandwidth can  create a “false center” phenomenon. This is an endogenous  bias because the algorithm performs its function correctly,  yet the output is a fiction. The ethical risk is clear: resources  could be diverted to these false centers of activity, leaving  the actual areas of high need underserved. Finally, at the interpretation level, endogenous bias arises  from the necessary act of data aggregation and grouping.  The choice of analytical units, whether spatial or non-spa - tial as illustrated in Fig. 2 (d), directly influences the con - clusions. This process can lead to endogenous bias, as the  chosen method of combining data for interpretation often  involves subjective decisions. The ethical danger of this  bias is significant. It opens the door for results to be shaped  to support a particular narrative, which can lead to forms  Fig. 2 ( a) illustrates Simpson’s paradox; (b) demonstrates endogenous  bias in spatial relationships and its ethical implications; (c) uses Kernel  Density Estimation (KDE) to exemplify biases induced by parameter  settings; (d) shows how different grouping strategies can lead to diver- gent conclusions   1 3 Page 5 of 31     4 Journal of Geovisualization and Spatial Analysis            (2026) 10:4  regions (A, B, and C), within which we simulated the occur- rence of Simpson’s Paradox in spatial analysis, as illustrated  in Fig. 4 (a). The synthetic dataset comprises 150 samples  (50 per region) with four variables, two numerical attributes  (“Variable 1” and “Variable 2”) and two spatial coordinates  (“X_coord” and “Y_coord”), constructed to represent distinct  regional patterns. In this experiment, “Variable 1” and “Variable 2” were set  to exhibit a positive correlation within each of three distinct  regions. Both grouped and overall regression analyses were  then performed on the data to evaluate the"
