   "id": "034",
   "source": {
    "title": "Multimodal deep learning from satellite and street-level imagery for measuring income, overcrowding, and environmental deprivation in urban areas",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2021.112339",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2021.112339",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2021",
    "abstract": "Data collected at large scale and low cost (e.g. satellite and street level imagery) have the potential to substantially improve resolution, spatial coverage, and temporal frequency of measurement of urban inequalities. Multiple types of data from different sources are often available for a given geographic area. Yet, most studies utilize a single type of input data when making measurements due to methodological difficulties in their joint use. We propose two deep learning-based methods for jointly utilizing satellite and street level imagery for measuring urban inequalities. We use London as a case study for three selected outputs, each measured in decile classes: income, overcrowding, and environmental deprivation. We compare the performances of our proposed multimodal models to corresponding unimodal ones using mean absolute error (MAE). First, satellite tiles are appended to street level imagery to enhance predictions at locations where street images are available leading to improvements in accuracy by 20, 10, and 9% in units of decile classes for income, overcrowding, and living environment. The second approach, novel to the best of our knowledge, uses a U-Net architecture to make predictions for all grid cells in a city at high spatial resolution (e.g. for 3 m × 3 m pixels in London in our experiments). It can utilize city wide availability of satellite images as well as more sparse information from street-level images where they are available leading to improvements in"
   },
   "report": "This audit examines a paper that introduces the SLinSAT model, utilizing deep learning models for population mapping and location-based inference algorithms. Technically, the research leverages the continuous coverage of satellite data to generate high-resolution (3-meter) city-wide maps of inequality, predicting socioeconomic indicators such as income, overcrowding, and environmental deprivation even where street-level imagery is missing. By creating granular tools designed to measure factors like air quality, traffic crash rates, and poor housing conditions to inform local government interventions, the work intersects with ethical domains concerning data privacy and geospatial fairness. \n\nThe auditor found no ethical risks actually instantiated by this paper's contribution; the identified concerns serve strictly as disclosures of category-level risks associated with the paper's techniques. As a potential disclosure, location-based inference algorithms operating at such high resolutions can theoretically enable the reconstruction of sensitive personal profiles. There is moderate confidence that, under the condition that this occurs without explicit user consent, such profile reconstruction could lead to privacy violations. Additionally, there is a strong categorical recognition that deep learning models used for population mapping can introduce population estimation bias, specifically under conditions of spatial heterogeneity—where spatial relationships vary across a landscape—and varying neighborhood sizes. If applied in the context of land use and resource management, there is moderate confidence that this bias could subsequently promote inequitable resource allocation stemming from misclassification. However, the paper itself does not perform actions that trigger these harms.\n\nBecause the identified risks remain uninstantiated, the text does not detail specific risk mitigations. In the overall auditor's judgment, zero risks are instantiated as audit findings, while four function merely as disclosures of potential, category-level vulnerabilities. Although the theoretical link between population mapping algorithms and estimation bias is strongly grounded as a general concern within GeoAI, this specific study does not actively trigger any of the ethical impacts discussed. The paper's contribution does not manufacture a harm narrative, and the auditor concludes that the research is largely ethics-silent regarding direct violations, with no actionable findings held against it.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (location-based inference algorithms:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (reconstruction of sensitive personal profiles:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n- (reconstruction of sensitive personal profiles:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Without explicit user consent)\n- (deep learning models for population mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Under conditions of spatial heterogeneity and varying neighborhood sizes)\n- (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable resource allocation from misclassification:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: location-based inference algorithms, deep learning models for population mapping\n  RiskMechanism: reconstruction of sensitive personal profiles, population estimation bias\n  EthicalImpact: privacy violation, inequitable resource allocation from misclassification",
