   "id": "037",
   "source": {
    "title": "LLM-enhanced disaster geolocalization using implicit geoinformation from multimodal data: A case study of Hurricane Harvey",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2025.104423",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2025.104423",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Timely and accurate geolocalization of natural disasters is crucial for effective emergency response, which is foundational for risk mitigation and resilience development. Although social media texts have been widely used to recognize and resolve disaster geolocations, the implicit geoinformation in social media images remains largely underexplored. In this paper, we propose a novel large language model (LLM)-enhanced disaster geolocalization method that considers both explicit and implicit geoinformation from multimodal data. Based on the recognition of geolocations in disaster-related images and texts, geolocalization results were obtained by combining LLMs with map services. The selection of a geolocalization strategy depends on the available geoinformation modality and the presence of spatial relationships. A multimodal dataset of 1,000 images and 1,000 texts from the Hurricane Harvey Twitter dataset was constructed to evaluate geolocalization accuracy through error distance. The results demonstrated that the proposed method achieves significant improvements over baseline geocoding and toponym retrieval methods, with overall accuracies of 81.45%, 78.40%, 74.60%, 65.20%, and 44.95% within 161, 100, 50, 10, and 1 km, respectively. These findings confirm the potential of LLMs in enhancing geolocalization by considering implicit geoinformation from multimodal data for future disaster response and broader GeoAI applications."
   },
   "report": "This paper technically utilizes large language models and geo-referencing techniques, specifically employing geocoding services to convert single geolocations found within images directly into precise geographic coordinates. Ethically, these technical features intersect heavily with data privacy concerns. The primary ethical touchpoints arise from the application of these models to social media data during high-stakes emergency scenarios, which can touch upon the exposure of sensitive user information. \n\nThe auditor’s causal risk reasoning distinguishes between actual risks triggered by the paper and broader category disclosures. There is one instantiated finding: the paper's active use of geo-referencing plausibly promotes privacy violations. Because the paper explicitly describes converting single image locations into geographic coordinates, this impact is considered an instantiated audit finding, albeit assessed with moderate confidence as a plausible rather than absolute outcome. Beyond this, the auditor notes two potential, category-level disclosures that this paper does not directly trigger. Specifically, large language models are associated with a potential risk of promoting the inference of mobility patterns and re-identification, but only under the condition that they are trained on massive volumes of geographic text and contextual data. Furthermore, such inference of mobility patterns has the potential to subsequently promote broader location privacy violations. These remain purely category-level disclosures regarding the inherent nature of LLMs, rather than actions performed by the authors.\n\nThe reviewed text does not introduce specific technical mitigations to neutralize these privacy concerns. In the overall auditor's judgment, out of the three identified causal pathways, only one risk is actually instantiated by the paper’s methodology, while the remaining two serve merely as potential disclosures regarding the broader use of large language models. The single instantiated finding—that geo-referencing promotes privacy violations—is moderately grounded in the text, representing a plausible ethical consequence of the coordinate conversion process utilized by the researchers.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (large language models:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inference of mobility patterns and re-identification:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When trained on massive volumes of geographic text and contextual data)\n- (inference of mobility patterns and re-identification:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (location privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n- (geo-referencing:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: large language models, geo-referencing\n  RiskMechanism: inference of mobility patterns and re-identification\n  EthicalImpact: location privacy violation, privacy violation",
