   "id": "039",
   "source": {
    "title": "Deep learning and automatic reference label harvesting for Sentinel-1 SAR-based rapid tropical dry forest disturbance mapping",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2023.113799",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2023.113799",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "The advent of temporally dense radar data such as the Sentinel-1 SAR have opened the door for rapid forest disturbance detection in the humid tropics. Tropical dry forest disturbance detection, however, were challenged by seasonality and more open canopy characteristics. In this manuscript, we proposed a Sentinel-1 SAR and deep learning based rapid forest disturbance detection approach for tropical dry forests. We demonstrated a weakly supervised method for reference label harvesting based on medium resolution globally available forest and forest disturbance maps. We trained a deep neural network model to derive forest and forest disturbance probabilities from Sentinel-1 images in the first step. We then implemented a probabilistic disturbance detection and refinement method to map forest disturbances in near real-time in two test regions in Paraguay and Mozambique. We mapped new forest disturbances in an emulated near real-time scenario for 2020 and 2021 and evaluated the spatial accuracy of the disturbance alerts by generating area adjusted precision, recall and F-1 score. We also evaluated the improvement in timeliness of disturbance detection by estimating mean time difference of disturbance events detection with that of Landsat-based GLAD alerts. The generated alerts in Paraguay and Mozambique achieved a precision, recall and F-1 score of 0.99, 0.61, 0.75 and 0.97, 0.51, 0.66, respectively. The proposed method detected disturbances with a mean of 21 days ( ± 18 days) ear"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a rapid, probabilistic disturbance detection and refinement method designed to map forest disturbances in near real-time across test regions in Paraguay and Mozambique. Technically, the authors utilize weakly supervised label harvesting to synthesize training labels from noisy global datasets, which are then processed by a Deep Neural Network featuring hidden layers, Batch Normalization, ReLU activation, and Dropout. By designing AI tools for operational remote sensing and continuous alert generation in environmentally and socially relevant regions, the methodology intersects with ethical domains concerning algorithmic transparency, systemic bias, and reliance on automated systems in Earth Observation contexts. \n\nThe audit identifies one actualized ethical risk explicitly triggered by the paper's methodology, alongside several broader category disclosures. There is a strongly grounded, instantiated finding that the paper’s focus on process automation with reduced human intervention promotes automation bias, specifically under the condition of generating continuous probabilistic alerts. However, the subsequent risk that this automation bias might lead to the misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data—potentially causing economic loss—remains a strong but strictly potential disclosure, as it is conditional on downstream overreliance on AI results without local expertise rather than the paper's direct actions. Other moderate potential disclosures relate to the general use of deep neural networks: their black-box nature can lead to a lack of algorithmic transparency when applied without explainability layers, which might theoretically promote safety risks in high-risk critical remote sensing missions. Similarly, there is a moderate potential disclosure that general AI technology development lacking integration with the humanities can introduce bias; if detection disparities occur, this bias could conditionally lead to systematic discrimination affecting vulnerable groups in regions targeted for monitoring. \n\nThe extracted text does not identify explicit mitigations deployed by the authors to neutralize these specific potential risks, such as the inclusion of explainability layers or systemic humanities integration. Overall, the auditor judges that of the six identified causal pathways, only one risk is actually instantiated by this paper, while the remaining five serve purely as category-level disclosures. The single instantiated finding—automation bias—is strongly grounded in the paper's near real-time probabilistic alerting framework. The uninstantiated disclosures highlight broader disciplinary hazards regarding transparency, economic loss, and systematic discrimination that, while highly relevant to remote sensing applications, are conditional and not directly triggered by the localized technical contributions of this study.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When applied without explainability layers)\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (process automation with reduced human intervention:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (automation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When generating continuous probabilistic alerts)\n- (automation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Overreliance on AI results without local expertise)\n- (ai technology:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Development lacking integration with the humanities)\n- (bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systematic discrimination:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When detection disparities disproportionately affect vulnerable groups)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box nature of deep neural networks, process automation with reduced human intervention, ai technology\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, automation bias, bias\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions, misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data, systematic discrimination",
