   "id": "041",
   "source": {
    "title": "Perspectives on spatio-temporal intelligence",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2025.12.011",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2025.12.011",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "The physical world, governed by the perpetual dynamics of matter, is inherently structured by spatio-temporal information. In the current Intelligence Era, rapid advances in data collection and Artificial Intelligence (AI) technologies have enabled large-scale acquisition and analysis of dynamic spatio-temporal information. These developments have led to the emergence of Spatio-Temporal Intelligence (STI), an interdisciplinary field that integrates spatio-temporal data with AI-driven computational methodologies to model, interpret, and manage complex physical, environmental, and social processes. In this paper, we offer a perspective on the mission and evolving scope of STI and identify its critical challenges. A general STI framework comprising five interconnected components is proposed to support adaptive observation, multi-modal modeling, causal reasoning, and knowledge-driven service delivery. Through a case study in national park ecological monitoring, we demonstrate how STI enables large-scale, precise, and real-time environmental understanding. Distinct from approaches that simulate symbolic or linguistic cognition, STI is grounded in the physical world and leverages high-dimensional sensor data to enable machine perception, foster new cognitive paradigms, and enhance decision-making across domains."
   },
   "report": "The technical contribution of this paper involves the use of deep neural networks—specifically Spatio-temporal Graph Neural Networks (ST-GNNs) and Spatio-temporal Transformers with convolutional LSTMs—alongside geo-referencing techniques integrating GNSS and Rational Polynomial Coefficients. These technical features are applied to various GeoAI modeling domains, including real-time surveillance for disaster and safety management, as well as the quantification of socioeconomic dynamics for urban and economic management. By operating in these domains, the paper's methodology intersects with several broad areas of ethical concern, primarily concerning model transparency, demographic modeling, and spatial data handling.\n\nThe auditor found no ethical risk actually instantiated by this paper's contribution; the findings are at most disclosures of category-level risk, and the paper is ultimately ethics-silent regarding direct harm. As a baseline disclosure, the black-box nature of deep neural networks promotes a potential lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability. Under the condition of high-risk remote sensing applications, such as critical disaster response, this opacity is plausibly linked to broader safety risks in critical missions. Similarly, the paper's reliance on GeoAI modeling belongs to a class of techniques that can suffer from collinearity between geographic location and protected characteristics like race and ethnicity. Under the specific condition where location is used as a proxy for social demographics, this collinearity could theoretically promote systematic discrimination. Finally, the foundational use of geo-referencing is broadly associated with potential privacy violations. However, the paper does not perform the triggering actions for any of these harms.\n\nBecause the paper does not actively trigger any of these causal risk mechanisms, no specific mitigations are present or required in the text. In the overall auditor's judgment, out of the five extracted risk pathways, zero are instantiated findings and all five serve merely as contextual disclosures. The paper safely employs complex geospatial architectures without manufacturing direct ethical violations, meaning the identified vulnerabilities regarding physical harm, equal rights violations, and privacy remain strictly potential vulnerabilities of the broader technical domain rather than faults of this specific work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (GeoAI modeling:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (collinearity between geographic location and protected characteristics raceethnicity:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When location is used as a proxy for social demographics)\n- (collinearity between geographic location and protected characteristics raceethnicity:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systematic discrimination:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n- (geo-referencing:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box nature of deep neural networks, GeoAI modeling, geo-referencing\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, collinearity between geographic location and protected characteristics raceethnicity\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions, systematic discrimination, privacy violation",
