     "content": "shattered gradients problem by averaging gradients over a large number of features across DNN layers but can  distort the activation of boundaries in the original datasets (e.g., the spatial extent of a runway). Gradients are a  good example of how XAI is more often used for model tuning than for preserving an object's structure as a means  of explanation. Two improved versions of CAM, Grad-  CAM (Selvaraju et al., 2017) and Grad-  CAM++ (Chattopadhay  et al., 2018) can handle spatial context surrounding an activated feature. The Class Activation Mapping (CAM)  gradient method visualizes the correlation between image regions and the specific area activated by the class  labels (Selvaraju et al., 2017). Grad- CAM++ (Chattopadhay et al.,  2018) weights the average of gradients of pixels  to create hotspots surrounding the activated part of an object. Grad-  CAM++ provides salient features of spatially  relevant regions of the input image because it draws on information across the image. Gradient-  based XAI meth - ods are constantly emerging (Lin et al., 2021), which could increase spatial context while preserving geographic  structures. 5 |  CHALLENGES INTRODUCED BY GeoAI Here we consider the difficulties in AI that cannot accommodate geographic data structures and which can be  compounded by XAI. As a result, the explanation may be insufficient for GeoAI. This section includes accommo - dating scale, handling topology and geometry, and reconciling different conceptions of mapping. These could be  a mixture of model-  agnostic and model-  specific XAIs. As GeoXAI relies on geographic structure and knowledge  in the explanation, we argue that these additions will inevitably shift usage from model-  agnostic XAI approaches  towards model-  specific, or even location-  specific model explanations. 5.1 | Challenges in accommodating spatial scale Scale is an innate concept in GIScience and plays a pivotal role in GeoAI (Kang et al., 2019; Liu & Biljecki, 2022).  The"
