   "source": {
    "title": "Monitoring direct drivers of small-scale tropical forest disturbance in near real-time with Sentinel-1 and -2 data",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2023.113655",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2023.113655",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Advancements in satellite-based forest monitoring increasingly enable the near real-time detection of small-scale tropical forest disturbances. However, there is an urgent need to enhance such monitoring methods with automated direct driver attributions to detected disturbances. This would provide important additional information to make forest disturbance alerts more actionable and useful for uptake by different stakeholders. In this study, we demonstrate spatially explicit and near real-time methods to monitor direct drivers of small-scale tropical forest disturbance across a range of tropical forest conditions in Suriname, the Republic of the Congo and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. We trained a convolutional neural network with Sentinel-1 and Sentinel-2 data to continuously classify newly detected RAdar for Detecting Deforestation (RADD) alerts as smallholder agriculture, road development, selective logging, mining or other. Different monitoring scenarios were evaluated based on varying sensor combinations, post-disturbance time periods and confidence levels. In general, the use of Sentinel-2 data was found to be most accurate for driver classifications, especially with data composited over a period of 4 to 6 months after the disturbance detection. Sentinel-1 data showed to be valuable for more rapid classifications of specific drivers, especially in areas with persistent cloud cover. Throughout all monitoring scenarios, smallholder agriculture was classified most "
   },
   "report": "Technically, this paper develops a system to continuously classify newly detected deforestation alerts—identifying activities such as smallholder agriculture, road development, selective logging, or mining—using Sentinel-1 and Sentinel-2 satellite imagery. To achieve this, the authors train a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) based on a simplified VGG-16 architecture. From an ethical auditing perspective, the primary trigger point is the system's reliance on deep neural networks, which introduces the inherent black-box nature of such models into an Earth observation pipeline designed to trigger rapid responses to illegal environmental activities.\n\nBy deploying this architecture, the paper actively instantiates a plausible ethical risk concerning algorithmic opacity. It is moderately certain that the black-box nature of the employed CNN promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability within the study's classification methodology. Beyond this instantiated finding, the auditor notes a broader category-level disclosure associated with this class of models: a lack of algorithmic transparency can potentially promote safety risks in critical missions resulting in physical harm. However, this downstream impact only actualizes under the condition that the system is used in high-risk remote sensing applications. Because the paper's technique is associated with this broader risk but does not actively execute critical, high-risk physical operations itself, this safety concern is reported strictly as a potential disclosure rather than an instantiated finding against the authors' work.\n\nThe extracted evidence does not detail any mitigating measures implemented to address the transparency limitations of the deployed model. In the auditor's overall judgment, the paper's instantiated ethical footprint is limited to a single, moderately grounded risk regarding the lack of algorithmic explainability inherent to its classification network. The secondary concern regarding safety in critical missions serves solely as a contextual disclosure of what the technique could raise in specific conditional scenarios that the paper does not currently trigger. Ultimately, the methodology instantiates a bounded algorithmic transparency issue while avoiding the direct manifestation of broader physical safety harms.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions",
