   "source": {
    "title": "Progressive multi-task graph neural network with multi-dimensional spatial feature fusion for building age prediction",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2026.105290",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2026.105290",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Accurate acquisition of building age information is of significant importance for understanding urban conditions. However, existing building age prediction methods face several challenges, including insufficient consideration of multi-dimensional spatial features, imbalanced sample distribution, and inadequate extraction of deep semantic features. To address these issues, this study designed a progressive multi-task learning-based graph neural network (PMTGNN) framework. First, the study innovatively integrates multi-source geospatial data to construct a multi-dimensional feature indicator system encompassing building geometric scale, building visual scale, resident perception scale, and socioeconomic scale. Based on this, graph-structured node representations are constructed to achieve comprehensive integration of building-related features. Second, the study introduces two auxiliary tasks (building height estimation and building function classification) to enhance the model’s generalization capability under sample imbalance conditions through knowledge transfer. Third, the study designs a progressive learning strategy, which leverages the synergistic effects of expert modules and gating networks to guide the model in gradually learning high-level semantic features from low-level building geometric features. Finally, taking Changzhou as an empirical case study, the study trained the model using existing building age data and filled in the missing age information for 51,281 bu"
   },
   "report": "This paper introduces a progressive multi-task learning-based graph neural network (PMTGNN) framework designed to predict building ages, particularly addressing informal or industrial constructions that often lack documentation. Technically, the study innovatively integrates multi-source geospatial data to construct a multi-dimensional feature indicator system, which encompasses building geometric scales, visual scales, resident perception scales, and socioeconomic scales. Ethically, the methodology interacts with fundamental concerns in GeoAI, specifically touching upon the inherent interpretability issues of complex modeling architectures and the broader data dynamics surrounding urban representation and geospatial inclusivity. \n\nRegarding specific causal risks, the auditor issues one instantiated finding: with moderate confidence, the paper’s implementation of a complex graph neural network promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability due to the inherently black-box nature of deep neural networks. Beyond this direct finding, the methodology belongs to a domain associated with other category-level risks that are disclosed here but not triggered by the paper itself. There is a moderately confident potential disclosure that algorithmic bias can promote marginalization and exclusion; however, this risk is conditional and generally applies only when the underlying data excludes vulnerable groups such as children, older adults, homeless individuals, or people with disabilities. This paper does not instantiate this exclusionary risk and instead seeks to provide a more inclusive view of the urban building stock.\n\nIn terms of systemic safeguards, the methodological class of this research includes protective capabilities. There is a strong-confidence potential disclosure that data integration and modeling can inhibit algorithmic bias, specifically under the condition that it is used to correct biases in crowdsourced or volunteered geographic information (VGI) datasets by combining multiple data sources. Overall, the auditor judges that only a single risk—the lack of algorithmic transparency inherent to the chosen neural network framework—is actually instantiated and moderately grounded by the paper’s technical contribution. The remaining observations regarding bias mitigation and marginalization serve purely as contextual disclosures of category-level risks, rather than actual ethical harms triggered by this study.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (data integration and modeling:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When used to correct bias in crowdsourced or VGI datasets by combining multiple data sources.)\n- (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (marginalization and exclusion:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When data excludes children, older adults, homeless individuals, or people with disabilities.)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic bias, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: marginalization and exclusion\n  Mitigation: data integration and modeling",
