   "source": {
    "title": "A Data-Driven framework for pedestrian oriented route planning leveraging deep learning and spatial perception",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2025.104932",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2025.104932",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Individuals make distinct walking choices based on the surrounding urban environment perceptions. Although a lot of work has been done in quantifying human perception of urban environment, existing research has not explored how the choices driven by perception can support walkability. This research aims to address this gap by proposing a framework that leverages 360-degree Google Street View Images (GSVIs), which serve as inputs to Deep Learning (DL) models. These models then extract informative features that contribute to the prediction of various perceptual attributes viz. beautiful, boring, safe, and lively collected through a primary survey. The attributes were integrated with road network at 100-meter intervals for the city of Mumbai, India. A multi-objective function is proposed to minimize the distance and maximize the perception to provide good routes. The DL models OCRNet and pretrained PPYOLOE + x achieved a high mIoU score of 72.13 %, and 51.4 %, respectively. Additionally, the state-of-art transformer-based model DINOv3 utilized for comparitive analysis and generalizability. The perception models also achieved a high accuracy of over 90%. Significant variations in routes were observed in diverse urban built-ups. The outcomes can support appropriate planning of urban spaces which can encourage walking, leading to reduction of carbon emissions."
   },
   "report": "The audited paper technically focuses on subjective spatial and non-spatial data grouping alongside the classification of informal settlements and slums. Specifically, the methodology maps subjective human perceptions—such as \"Safe,\" \"Beautiful,\" or \"Lively,\" modeled from global datasets like Place Pulse—onto local road networks at 100-meter intervals for the city of Mumbai. By employing a standard deviation-based thresholding task to filter out ambiguous mid-range perception scores, the authors identify specific clusters, including \"Low-Low\" perception areas that often correspond to informal settlements. Because the technique explicitly quantifies subjective human perceptions and structurally embeds them into urban spatial models and routing features, it touches directly on the ethical dimensions of how spatial data reflects and solidifies subjective human perspectives.\n\nIn evaluating the causal risk reasoning, the auditor identifies one plausibly instantiated finding alongside several potential category-level disclosures. With moderate confidence, the auditor concludes that the paper’s use of subjective spatial and non-spatial data grouping actively promotes the risk mechanism of subjective narrative reinforcement. Because the paper directly filters and projects these subjective scores onto Mumbai's road networks, this specific risk is genuinely triggered by the methodology. Beyond this instantiated finding, the technical approach belongs to a broader class of models associated with subsequent risks that this paper does not actually trigger. As a potential disclosure, subjective narrative reinforcement is broadly associated with statistical gerrymandering and social stereotype reinforcement, though the audited paper does not instantiate this impact. Furthermore, the paper's capability to classify informal settlements carries a potential risk of promoting territorial stigmatization, but strictly under the condition that such sensitive maps are published without care for local consequences. If that condition were met and the stigmatization affected public perception and policy, it could theoretically promote forced evictions and displacement. However, the auditor stresses that these downstream economic and equal-rights impacts are purely potential disclosures regarding the method's broader category, not harms triggered by this paper's actions.\n\nThe evaluated text does not present explicit ethical mitigations to neutralize these specific pathways. The overall auditor's judgement distinguishes clearly between theoretical vulnerabilities and the paper's actual executed contribution. Out of four identified risk pathways, only one—the mechanism of subjective narrative reinforcement—is actually instantiated as an audit finding, grounded with moderate confidence based on the paper's direct integration of subjective thresholds into municipal spatial mapping. The remaining three items are strictly potential disclosures. Therefore, while the paper plausibly risks reinforcing subjective narratives through its technical pipeline, the more severe downstream risks of territorial stigmatization, displacement, and statistical gerrymandering remain uninstantiated category warnings rather than direct ethical violations committed by this work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (classification of informal settlements and slums:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (Territorial stigmatization:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When sensitive maps are published without care for local consequences)\n- (Territorial stigmatization:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (forced evictions and displacement:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When stigmatization affects public perception and policy)\n- (subjective spatial and non-spatial data grouping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (subjective narrative reinforcement:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (subjective narrative reinforcement:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (statistical gerrymandering and social stereotype reinforcement:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: classification of informal settlements and slums, subjective spatial and non-spatial data grouping\n  RiskMechanism: Territorial stigmatization, subjective narrative reinforcement\n  EthicalImpact: forced evictions and displacement, statistical gerrymandering and social stereotype reinforcement",
