   "id": "051",
   "source": {
    "title": "Deep Learning and Multi Source 2D and 3D Geospatial Data for Urban Quality of Life Assessment",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2025.104838",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2025.104838",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Urban Quality of Life (UQoL) assessment is essential for improving well-being and guiding urban planning. While most studies focus on developed countries using household surveys and satellite imagery, this study addresses the gaps pertaining to the quantification of UQoL at a very microscale by utilizing multi-modal 2D and 3D data, viz. elevation-stacked Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV) imagery, Google Street View (GSV) imagery, and amenities information derived from crowdsourced OpenStreetMap (OSM). An Unsupervised Domain Adaptation (UDA) based Deep Learning (DL) pipeline is implemented to segment UAV imagery, extracting indicators like built-up and green cover from the segmentation maps. Additionally, DeepLabV3 is used to segment GSV imagery to compute the sky-view factor, while OSM is employed to extract the location information of amenities. The UDA-based ResiDualGAN, equipped with a convolutional resizer model and integrated with the OSA method, trained on the RGB-nDSM dataset, achieved an IoU of 60.48%. Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is applied to create a weighted UQoL index. The results reveal disparities in UQoL across the study area, with higher UQoL in green, amenity-rich regions, emphasizing the importance of utility access. Notably, informal settlements located near essential services exhibited high UQoL despite having limited green cover and higher built-up density, which clearly emphasizes the importance of proximity as a key indicator of UQoL."
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a framework designed to measure the quality of life within informal regions and slums, utilizing microscale indexing to simulate redevelopment projects and identify underserved regions for the allocation of new infrastructure. Technically, the method relies on the classification of informal settlements and the mapping of urban areas using a granular 100m by 100m spatial grid to capture variance across neighborhoods. By focusing on vulnerable settlements, identifying underserved locations, and simulating infrastructure impacts, the paper’s technical contributions touch upon ethical domains concerning the representation of marginalized communities and the equitable distribution of urban resources. \n\nThe auditor found no ethical risks actually instantiated by this paper's specific contributions; the identified concerns exist solely as potential, category-level disclosures. Plausibly, the classification of informal settlements and slums is associated with the promotion of territorial stigmatization, though this risk only materializes under the condition that sensitive maps are published without care for local consequences. In turn, if territorial stigmatization were to negatively affect public policy and perception, it could potentially promote forced evictions and displacement, thereby violating equal rights. A separate category-level risk involves flawed policy impacts on marginalized communities resulting from the masking of subpopulation conditions. However, this masking risk is not triggered by the paper: the hazard typically arises only when heterogeneous spatial data is treated uniformly and aggregated without accounting for subpopulation variance, a practice this paper explicitly avoids. \n\nAs a mitigation, the paper averts the masking of subpopulation conditions by conducting its analysis at a high-resolution microscale, successfully neutralizing the threat of treating diverse spatial data as uniform. Overall, the auditor concludes that out of the four identified causal risk pathways, zero are instantiated by the paper’s actions. The potential harms discussed remain merely theoretical disclosures related to the general classification of slums and spatial mapping. Because the paper actively mitigates data aggregation risks and does not trigger any of the remaining pathways, it is fundamentally ethics-silent regarding these harms, generating no actual audit findings against its methodology.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (classification of informal settlements and slums:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (Territorial stigmatization:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When sensitive maps are published without care for local consequences)\n- (Territorial stigmatization:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (forced evictions and displacement:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When stigmatization affects public perception and policy)\n- (treating heterogeneous spatial data as uniform:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (masking of subpopulation conditions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>  (when: When distinct regions are aggregated without accounting for subpopulation variance)\n- (masking of subpopulation conditions:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (flawed policy impacting marginalized communities:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: classification of informal settlements and slums, treating heterogeneous spatial data as uniform\n  RiskMechanism: Territorial stigmatization, masking of subpopulation conditions\n  EthicalImpact: forced evictions and displacement, flawed policy impacting marginalized communities",
