   "id": "057",
   "source": {
    "title": "Mapping invasive Opuntia stricta in Kenya's Drylands using explainable machine learning with time-series remote sensing and geographic context",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2025.104867",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2025.104867",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Opuntia stricta is a globally widespread invasive species that degrades dryland ecosystems and threatens pastoral livelihoods. Accurate, high-resolution distribution maps are essential for effective management, but its spectral similarity to native vegetation complicates remote sensing-based classification. We developed an interpretable Random Forest model, incorporating SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP), to map Opuntia stricta and co-occurring land cover types at 10 m resolution across heterogeneous arid and semi-arid lands in Laikipia County, Kenya. The model integrated monthly Sentinel-2 imagery, climate, topographic, landscape structural, and anthropogenic factors. Field surveys were combined with manual labeling using Google Maps and Street View to address annotation gaps in remote areas. Grid-based spatial blocking at multiple scales was used to reduce spatial autocorrelation and assess generalizability. The multi-temporal model achieved 0.91 overall accuracy and an F1-score of 0.92 for Opuntia stricta on the spatial validation set (100 m grid), and 0.86 accuracy with an F1-score of 0.85 on the independent test set, substantially outperforming single-month models (accuracy: 0.62–0.79; F1: 0.67–0.82), with February identified as the most informative single-time window. SHAP analysis identified July precipitation, population density and nighttime land surface temperatures as top predictors, linking invasion patterns to dry-season aridity, wet-season rainfall, and warm "
   },
   "report": "This paper presents an ecological mapping methodology that utilizes a Random Forest model to map the invasive species *Opuntia stricta* and co-occurring land cover types at a 10-meter resolution across heterogeneous lands. To understand the drivers behind these invasion patterns, the authors technically integrate SHapley Additive exPlanations (SHAP)—an Explainable AI (XAI) algorithm that quantitatively measures the attribution of spatial features to model outcomes—to identify top predictors such as population density, land surface temperatures, and precipitation. By evaluating these explainable AI results alongside socio-ecological disparities, noting that communal group ranches experience heavier invasions than private conservancies, the research touches upon the ethical dimensions of algorithmic transparency and the handling of sensitive demographic associations. \n\nIn analyzing the causal risk reasoning, the auditor notes that this study does not actively trigger any negative ethical impacts; rather, it prompts disclosures regarding the broader technological category. There is a strong potential that utilizing explainable AI results can promote the risk mechanism of group re-identification, but strictly under the condition that the model is explaining outcomes involving marginalized groups. Furthermore, there is a moderately grounded potential that such group re-identification could subsequently promote individual and group privacy violations. However, because this specific paper leverages XAI to analyze environmental invasion patterns rather than identifying protected human subjects, these privacy and re-identification risks serve solely as category-level disclosures. The techniques belong to a class of methods that can raise these concerns in human-centric contexts, but this paper firmly does not instantiate them.\n\nConversely, the paper does successfully instantiate a robust ethical mitigation. The auditor finds strong evidence that the study's commitment to transparency actively inhibits the inability to audit black-box model decisions, fulfilling the necessary condition that algorithmic processes are made interpretable. Ultimately, the auditor's judgment is that out of three identified causal pathways, only one is actually instantiated, and it is a strongly grounded, positive mitigation. The remaining two pathways represent purely theoretical, potential disclosures regarding XAI and privacy risks that remain entirely un-triggered by this paper's specific contributions.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (explainable ai xai results:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (group re-identification:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When explaining outcomes involving marginalized groups)\n- (group re-identification:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (individual and group privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n- (transparency:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (inability to audit black-box model decisions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: when processes are made interpretable)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: explainable ai xai results\n  RiskMechanism: group re-identification, inability to audit black-box model decisions\n  EthicalImpact: individual and group privacy violation\n  Mitigation: transparency",
