   "source": {
    "title": "Spatially explicit accuracy assessment of deep learning-based, fine-resolution built-up land data in the United States",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2023.103469",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2023.103469",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Geospatial datasets derived from remote sensing data by means of machine learning methods are often based on probabilistic outputs of abstract nature, which are difficult to translate into interpretable measures. For example, the Global Human Settlement Layer GHS-BUILT-S2 product reports the probability of the presence of built-up areas in 2018 in a global 10 m × 10 m grid. However, practitioners typically require interpretable measures such as binary surfaces indicating the presence or absence of built-up areas or estimates of sub-pixel built-up surface fractions. Herein, we assess the relationship between the built-up probability in GHS-BUILT-S2 and reference built-up surface fractions derived from a highly reliable reference database for several regions in the United States. Furthermore, we identify a binarization threshold using an agreement maximization method that creates binary built-up land data from these built-up probabilities. These binary surfaces are input to a spatially explicit, scale-sensitive accuracy assessment which includes the use of a novel, visual-analytical tool which we call focal precision-recall signature plots. Our analysis reveals that a threshold of 0.5 applied to GHS-BUILT-S2 maximizes the agreement with binarized built-up land data derived from the reference built-up area fraction. We find high levels of accuracy (i.e., county-level F-1 scores of almost 0.8 on average) in the derived built-up areas, and consistently high accuracy along the rura"
   },
   "report": "The technical scope of the evaluated paper centers on the application of deep learning models for population mapping and the use of spatially-explicit performance evaluation techniques, such as hot and cold spot detection for geoparsers. The ethical touchpoints of these domain technologies emerge from how accurately computational models characterize populations under conditions of spatial heterogeneity, as well as how spatial evaluation metrics either capture or obscure localized error patterns across different geographic regions. \n\nThe auditor found no ethical risks actually instantiated by this paper's direct contribution; therefore, all identified causal mechanisms serve strictly as disclosures of broader category-level risks rather than active findings against this research. Within this broader technical class, deep learning models applied to population mapping carry a moderately grounded, potential risk of promoting population estimation bias, specifically under conditions of spatial heterogeneity and varying neighborhood sizes. If such models are relied upon to facilitate resource allocation and disaster preparedness, this estimation bias could plausibly promote the inequitable distribution of resources and services. Furthermore, there is a moderate potential risk that general evaluation bias might hide regional variability, which could subsequently reduce reliability and fairness in underserved regions during the deployment of geoparsers for downstream geospatial tasks.\n\nTo address such vulnerabilities, the broader methodological space outlines potential mitigations, noting that spatially-explicit performance evaluation—specifically hot and cold spot detection—can inhibit the risk of evaluation bias hiding regional variability by clearly exposing where a geoparser is biased towards or against. In the final auditor's judgement, zero risks are actually instantiated by the paper's methodology, while four represent potential disclosures associated with the broader class of mapping techniques. Because the paper does not actively trigger any of these harms, the auditor concludes that the research operates safely regarding its direct contributions, successfully avoiding the actualization of geospatial bias or inequity.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (deep learning models for population mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Under conditions of spatial heterogeneity and varying neighborhood sizes)\n- (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable resource and service distribution:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When models are used to facilitate resource allocation and disaster preparedness)\n- (spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: By exposing where a geoparser is biased towards or against)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of geoparsers for downstream geospatial tasks)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: deep learning models for population mapping\n  RiskMechanism: population estimation bias, evaluation bias hiding regional variability\n  EthicalImpact: inequitable resource and service distribution, reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions\n  Mitigation: spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection",
