   "id": "062",
   "source": {
    "title": "Most complicated lock pattern-based seismological signal framework for automated earthquake detection",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2023.103297",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2023.103297",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Background Seismic signals record earthquakes and also noise from different sources. The influence of noise makes it difficult to interpret seismograph signals correctly. This study aims to develop a computationally lightweight, accurate, and explainable machine learning model for the automated detection of seismogram signals that could serve as an effective warning system for earthquake prediction. Material and method We developed a handcrafted model for earthquake detection using a balanced dataset of 5001 earthquakes and 5001 non-earthquake signal samples. The model included multilevel feature extraction, selector-based feature selection, classification, and post-processing. Input signals were decomposed using tunable Q wave transform and fed to a statistical and textural feature extractor based on the most complicated lock pattern (MCLP). Four feature selectors were used to choose the most valuable features for the support vector machine classifier. Additionally, voted vectors were generated using iterative hard majority voting. Finally, the best model was chosen using a greedy algorithm. Results The presented self-organized MCLP-based feature engineering model yielded 96.82% classification accuracy with 10-fold cross-validation using the seismic signal dataset. Conclusions Our model attained high seismological signal detection performance comparable with more computationally expensive deep learning models. Our handcrafted explainable feature engineering model is computat"
   },
   "report": "This paper technically contributes a self-organized, explainable AI (XAI) framework utilizing handcrafted feature engineering for earthquake detection. By providing a computationally efficient model with linear time complexity, the authors intersect with ethical dimensions regarding model transparency in seismological analysis. The framework's core ethical touchpoint lies in its deliberate departure from opaque machine learning approaches, focusing instead on allowing end-users to interpret the specific statistical and textural signal features that drive the automated detection process. \n\nIn evaluating the causal risk landscape, the auditor notes that the ethical dynamics center entirely on resolving opacity rather than introducing new algorithmic harms. As a moderately grounded, instantiated finding, the paper's explicit integration of transparency actively inhibits the inability to audit black-box model decisions. This functional benefit operates conditionally, specifically holding true when processes are made sufficiently interpretable for seismologists to evaluate the underlying detection logic. Furthermore, a potential category-level disclosure is observed: explainable AI methods generally inhibit hidden security hazards inherently associated with black-box models, conditional upon their deployment in high-risk geoscience and remote sensing applications. This broader security dynamic is reported merely as a potential disclosure associated with the technique's broader class, rather than a discrete mechanism triggered or uniquely resolved by this study's specific actions.\n\nThe primary mitigations are embedded directly within the paper's technical architecture, utilizing explainable feature engineering to avert auditing deficits and potentially increase human trust in warning systems. Overall, the auditor identifies zero instantiated negative risk mechanisms generated by the authors' method; rather, the assessment yields exactly one instantiated finding—which demonstrates the active mitigation of model auditing challenges—and one potential disclosure regarding the broader inhibition of security hazards. Because the instantiated finding relies on the paper's claimed operational interpretability, it is assessed with moderate confidence, reflecting a plausible, structurally sound approach to responsible and transparent AI development in seismology.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (explainable ai:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (hidden security hazards in black box models:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In high-risk GRS applications)\n- (transparency:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (inability to audit black-box model decisions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: when processes are made interpretable)\n\nEntities by type:\n  RiskMechanism: hidden security hazards in black box models, inability to audit black-box model decisions\n  Mitigation: explainable ai, transparency",
