   "source": {
    "title": "Human-in-the-loop based framework for solid waste dumps detection in remote sensing images",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2026.105133",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2026.105133",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Detecting solid waste dumps (SWDs) is crucial for a sustainable environment and public health. Deep learning methods have demonstrated significant potential in detecting SWDs from high-spatial resolution remote sensing images (RSIs). However, training a SWD detection model necessitates annotated data that encompasses diverse geographical distributions and styles. Following the conventional approach of manually labeling data prior to model training is both costly and time-consuming. In this study, we propose a human-in-the-loop framework for the detection of SWDs. An initial model is trained using public datasets of Dumpsites, solid waste aerial detection (SWAD), and AerialWaste to identify potential samples from extensive unlabeled RSIs, which are then validated by experts for data expansion and model reinforcement. Specifically, multi-view inference is introduced to enhance the applicability of the model for real-world SWD detection tasks by integrating inference results from multiple style-transformed images. Moreover, we utilize adaptive thresholds that are dynamically calculated from inference results in each round to select potential SWDs, all while maintaining a low computational cost. With the proposed framework, we construct the LHRS-SWD dataset for SWD detection, derived from a random sampling of over 70 countries and encompassing 3,377 SWDs. The effectiveness of our framework is validated through experiments on LHRS-SWD, with a 20.26% improvement in AP50 versus init"
   },
   "report": "Technically, the paper focuses on the detection of solid waste disposal sites across diverse geographical distributions and visual styles to map the Global North-South divide in waste management. To accomplish this, the authors implement a human-in-the-loop framework characterized by a six-stage iterative process. This process identifies candidate sites using initial models trained on public data, which are then filtered via adaptive thresholds and refined through a rigorous two-stage expert validation system involving scoring by multiple experts and a veto process by a senior expert. The core ethical intersection of this work lies in how this human-centered design evaluates and curates the dataset to manage the diverse geographical characteristics of the targeted solid waste sites. \n\nIn terms of causal risk reasoning, the auditor finds it plausible that the paper's instantiated human-in-the-loop and human-centered design actively inhibits the risk mechanism of representational bias and exclusion, specifically under the condition that these interventions occur during the design of the GeoAI systems and algorithms. Furthermore, the downstream risk of representational bias promoting systemic spatial injustice and inequity is successfully neutralized and not triggered by this work; instead of exacerbating spatial divides, the paper explicitly maps these areas to highlight where international aid and technology transfer for waste disposal are most needed. As a broader category disclosure, human-in-the-loop GeoAI is also associated with the potential to inhibit unethical or inaccurate machine-generated maps—which could theoretically lead to physical harm—under the condition that cartographers are allowed to intervene in output quality and visual assessment. However, this specific pathway remains a category-level disclosure of the technique's potential rather than an instantiated finding for this paper.\n\nOverall, the auditor concludes that there are no ethical risks actually instantiated by this paper's contribution. The paper relies heavily on built-in mitigations, utilizing its expert verification framework to actively improve performance and avoid the representational pitfalls common in global mapping tasks. Out of the three evaluated causal pathways, one positive mitigation is actually instantiated with moderate grounding, one severe risk of spatial injustice is explicitly avoided, and one broader risk-reduction capability is disclosed as a potential feature of the method class. Ultimately, the findings highlight an ethics-aware approach where potential harms are preempted by robust, human-guided validation.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (human-centered design and human-in-the-loop:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (representational bias and exclusion:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: During the design of GeoAI systems and algorithms)\n- (representational bias and exclusion:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (systemic spatial injustice and inequity:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>\n- (human-in-the-loop geoai:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (unethical or inaccurate machine-generated maps:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: By allowing cartographers to intervene in output quality and visual assessment)\n\nEntities by type:\n  RiskMechanism: representational bias and exclusion\n  EthicalImpact: systemic spatial injustice and inequity, unethical or inaccurate machine-generated maps\n  Mitigation: human-centered design and human-in-the-loop, human-in-the-loop geoai",
