   "id": "065",
   "source": {
    "title": "Global reconstruction of three decades of fine-grained nighttime light data with analysis of large-scale infrastructure and landmarks",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2025.115036",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2025.115036",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Satellite-collected nighttime light provides a unique perspective on human activities, including urbanization, population growth, and epidemics. However, global, long-term, and fine-grained nighttime light observations are lacking, hindering the analysis and application of continuous light changes in specific facilities over extended periods. To address this gap, we reformulated the super-resolution task – reconstructing low-resolution nighttime light data into high-resolution images – by explicitly incorporating temporal difference information. Rigorous validation across three evaluation years demonstrates that our dataset consistently outperforms existing products at global, national, and city scales. Case studies of high-value infrastructure sites, such as artificial islands and international airports, highlight our dataset’s unprecedented ability to capture both long-term gradual illumination changes associated with development and abrupt intensity oscillations caused by wars. The dataset is available at https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.15845676."
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a technical framework designed to reconstruct DMSP-OLS satellite data into NPP-VIIRS-like high-resolution imagery using a proposed deep learning model called DeepNTL. The technical contributions involve two primary features that serve as ethical triggers: the inherent black-box nature of the applied deep neural networks, and the collection of highly detailed temporal geodata. Notably, the paper utilizes these technical features to create a dataset capable of capturing both long-term gradual illumination changes associated with development and abrupt intensity oscillations caused by wars, explicitly testing the method on high-value infrastructure sites such as artificial islands and international airports. \n\nThe auditor identifies two instantiated ethical risks directly stemming from the paper's methodology, alongside one category-level disclosure. First, with strong confidence, the auditor finds that the detailed temporal geodata collection promotes the risk of oppressive surveillance, specifically when deployed under the condition of civil strife or contested territories. Second, the reliance on deep neural networks instantiates a moderately confident risk finding: the black-box nature of the DeepNTL model plausibly leads to a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability. Beyond these direct findings, the auditor notes one potential disclosure regarding the broader category of this technique. While not instantiated by the paper's specific actions, a lack of algorithmic transparency is generally known to promote safety risks in critical missions—potentially leading to physical harm—under the condition that the technique is applied in high-risk remote sensing applications. \n\nThere are no mitigating measures present within the evaluated material to offset these identified concerns. In the overall judgment of the auditor, the paper yields two instantiated risk findings and one potential category disclosure. The most well-grounded instantiated finding is the strong risk of oppressive surveillance in contested territories, which is directly tied to the paper's unprecedented capability to track structural and temporal intensity oscillations during conflict. The secondary instantiated finding regarding algorithmic transparency remains moderately grounded as a plausible consequence of utilizing deep learning architectures. Ultimately, while the paper does not directly trigger downstream safety failures in critical operations, the actualized surveillance and transparency vulnerabilities warrant careful ethical consideration before operationalizing this high-resolution temporal tracking framework.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (detailed temporal geodata collection:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (oppressive surveillance:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: In contexts of civil strife or contested territory)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: black-box nature of deep neural networks, detailed temporal geodata collection\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, oppressive surveillance\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions",
