   "id": "068",
   "source": {
    "title": "Review on Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) in vegetation remote sensing",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2020.12.010",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2020.12.010",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2021",
    "abstract": "Identifying and characterizing vascular plants in time and space is required in various disciplines, e.g. in forestry, conservation and agriculture. Remote sensing emerged as a key technology revealing both spatial and temporal vegetation patterns. Harnessing the ever growing streams of remote sensing data for the increasing demands on vegetation assessments and monitoring requires efficient, accurate and flexible methods for data analysis. In this respect, the use of deep learning methods is trend-setting, enabling high predictive accuracy, while learning the relevant data features independently in an end-to-end fashion. Very recently, a series of studies have demonstrated that the deep learning method of Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) is very effective to represent spatial patterns enabling to extract a wide array of vegetation properties from remote sensing imagery. This review introduces the principles of CNN and distils why they are particularly suitable for vegetation remote sensing. The main part synthesizes current trends and developments, including considerations about spectral resolution, spatial grain, different sensors types, modes of reference data generation, sources of existing reference data, as well as CNN approaches and architectures. The literature review showed that CNN can be applied to various problems, including the detection of individual plants or the pixel-wise segmentation of vegetation classes, while numerous studies have evinced that CNN outp"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a methodology centered on deep learning frameworks, particularly Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), for analyzing vegetation from diverse remote sensing data sources. The technical approach involves leveraging the modularity of these frameworks to combine datasets such as optical imagery, SAR, and LiDAR. From an ethics perspective, the primary triggers for risk are the inherent `black-box nature of deep neural networks` and the capacity for `mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and ai`, which can create new informational products from existing sources.\n\nBased on these technical features, the audit identifies two risks as being instantiated by the paper's contribution. First, the reliance on CNNs gives rise to a `lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability`, a finding grounded with moderate confidence in the paper's own discussion of the need to interpret these models. Second, and more tentatively, a weakly-grounded finding suggests that the method for `mosaicking disparate geodata` could promote the `disclosure of sensitive geospatial data`, a risk that holds when the combination of seemingly unrelated datasets creates novel insights. Other risks are identified only as potential disclosures associated with this technology class, not as findings against this paper. For instance, the use of geographically limited training datasets from North America and Europe can lead to `population bias` and subsequent `resource allocation inequality` in land management contexts, though this paper does not appear to instantiate this chain. Similarly, the lack of transparency could potentially lead to `safety risks in critical missions`, and data disclosure could cause `location privacy violation`, but these impacts are not triggered by this work.\n\nThe paper acknowledges some of these issues and gestures toward potential mitigations. It utilizes visualization techniques like Class Activation Mapping (CAM) and Grad-CAM, which belong to a class of `structured evaluation frameworks` that can inhibit the `lack of algorithmic transparency`. Furthermore, its advocacy for federated learning points toward a category of privacy-preserving techniques, related to `geomasking`, that can inhibit the `disclosure of sensitive geospatial data`. In summary, this audit surfaces two instantiated findings—a moderately-grounded risk concerning transparency and a weakly-grounded, inferred risk of sensitive data disclosure. The remaining items are disclosures of potential risks that this paper does not activate.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (unrepresentative geographic training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When datasets fail to represent actual target regions)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (structured evaluation framework and quantifiable metrics:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Implementation during AI development and deployment)\n- (mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and ai:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (disclosure of sensitive geospatial data:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When combining seemingly unrelated datasets creates new information products)\n- (disclosure of sensitive geospatial data:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (location privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When exposing home locations, workspaces, and daily trajectories)\n- (Geomasking and spatial-temporal cloaking:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (disclosure of sensitive geospatial data:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: unrepresentative geographic training data, black-box nature of deep neural networks, mosaicking disparate geodata using spatial references and ai\n  RiskMechanism: population bias, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, disclosure of sensitive geospatial data\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, safety risks in critical missions, location privacy violation\n  Mitigation: structured evaluation framework and quantifiable metrics, Geomasking and spatial-temporal cloaking",
