   "id": "069",
   "source": {
    "title": "HyperLi-Net: A hyper-light deep learning network for high-accurate and high-speed ship detection from synthetic aperture radar imagery",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2020.05.016",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2020.05.016",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2020",
    "abstract": "Ship detection from Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) imagery is attracting increasing attention due to its great value in ocean. However, existing most studies are frequently improving detection accuracy at the expense of detection speed. Thus, to solve this problem, this paper proposes HyperLi-Net for high-accurate and high-speed SAR ship detection. We propose five external modules to achieve high-accuracy, i.e., Multi-Receptive-Field Module (MRF-Module), Dilated Convolution Module (DC-Module), Channel and Spatial Attention Module (CSA-Module), Feature Fusion Module (FF-Module) and Feature Pyramid Module (FP-Module). We also adopt five internal mechanisms to achieve high-speed, i.e., Region-Free Model (RF-Model), Small Kernel (S-Kernel), Narrow Channel (N-Channel), Separable Convolution (Separa-Conv) and Batch Normalization Fusion (BN-Fusion). Experimental results on the SAR Ship Detection Dataset (SSDD), Gaofen-SSDD and Sentinel-SSDD show that HyperLi-Net’s accuracy and speed are both superior to the other nine state-of-the-art methods. Moreover, the satisfactory detection results on two Sentinel-1 SAR images can reveal HyperLi-Net’s good migration capability. HyperLi-Net is build from scratch with fewer parameters, lower computation costs and lighter model that can be efficiently trained on CPUs and is helpful for future hardware transplantation, e.g. FPGAs, DSPs, etc."
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a deep learning-based SAR ship detector, HyperLi-Net, designed for high-accuracy and high-speed performance. The primary technical features that engage with ethical considerations are its construction as a complex, deep neural network and its potential application in real-time, on-board embedded systems for remote sensing. These aspects raise questions concerning algorithmic transparency, the reliability of the generated geospatial information, and the downstream uses of such real-time detection capabilities in critical domains.\n\nThe audit identifies plausible risks directly instantiated by this work. The model's foundation on a deep neural network architecture, characterized by its black-box nature, plausibly promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability. This opacity may, in turn, contribute to safety risks when the technology is deployed in high-risk remote sensing applications such as the maritime safety and tracking missions described. Furthermore, the use of a deep learning-based detector moderately suggests a risk of generating misleading geospatial information. Separately, the paper's technology belongs to a class of methods that could be associated with other harms, though these are not instantiated here. For instance, the general mechanism of generating misleading geospatial information could potentially lead to geospatial misinformation, particularly in sensitive political or cultural contexts. Similarly, real-time onboard SAR ship detection for embedded systems could promote lethal outcomes for combatants and non-combatants, but only under the condition of being used without human supervision, a scenario not explored in this paper.\n\nIn conclusion, this audit finds no mitigations presented within the scope of the analysis. The paper instantiates three ethical risks, all with moderate grounding, centered on the consequences of limited algorithmic transparency and the potential creation of misleading information, which can create safety risks in critical missions. In addition to these instantiated findings, the audit serves a disclosure function by noting two potential downstream harms related to misinformation and autonomous lethality, clarifying that while the technology class is associated with these risks, this paper's specific implementation does not trigger them.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (real-time onboard sar ship detection for embedded systems:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lethal outcomes for combatants and non-combatants:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: without human supervision)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (deep learning-based sar ship detector:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (generation of misleading geospatial information:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (generation of misleading geospatial information:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (geospatial misinformation:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: particularly in sensitive political or cultural contexts)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: real-time onboard sar ship detection for embedded systems, black-box nature of deep neural networks, deep learning-based sar ship detector\n  RiskMechanism: lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, generation of misleading geospatial information\n  EthicalImpact: lethal outcomes for combatants and non-combatants, safety risks in critical missions, geospatial misinformation",
