   "id": "070",
   "source": {
    "title": "Advanced wildfire detection using generative adversarial network-based augmented datasets and weakly supervised object localization",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2022.103052",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2022.103052",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2022",
    "abstract": "Owing to abnormal climate phenomena worldwide, forests are becoming dry and heat waves have started to occur, increasing the damage caused by wildfires. In addition to causing significant human and material damage, wildfires are also a major cause of critical pollutant emissions, in which fine dust generated by incomplete combustion pollutes the atmosphere, soil, and water. Early detection and monitoring are some of the main ways for minimizing wildfire damage, and a topic of research interest in various fields of artificial intelligence and computer vision. However, the lack of wildfire occurred image datasets is still challenge. Training deep learning model in this environment, can lead mis-detection when burning point is far from the camera or according to objects similar to flame and smoke. Our study attempted to create synthetic wildfire images in various shapes by inserting damage into a free-wildfire image using generative adversarial network (GAN) and Weakly supervised object localization (WSOL). The synthesized image can used as training data for object detection by applying the WSOL method with gradient-weighted activation map (Grad-CAM). Additionally, the YOLOv5s model was improved by adding a channel attention module; sequence-and-excitation (SE) layer and replace loss function as CIoU to address the issue of wildfire false detection in fire-like object and miss detection in small size smoke. Our proposed method, produced results as high as 7.19% in F1-score and 6"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a system for automated, real-time wildfire detection using a deep learning model. The technical approach touches upon ethical considerations through its use of geographically concentrated training data, specifically drone-captured images from Korean forests, and its application of Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) data augmentation to create synthetic wildfire images. The system's core function is to identify wildfires in real-time, which inherently engages with high-stakes decision-making in emergency situations.\n\nBased on the evidence, this audit finds it plausible that the paper's methodology instantiates certain risks. The use of geographically concentrated training data from Korea promotes a risk of geographic representation bias, a condition that becomes salient when a model trained on these specific regional datasets is deployed in unrepresented ecosystems with different environmental characteristics. Furthermore, the nature of an automated real-time detection system introduces a plausible risk of incorrect predictions, particularly when the model misinterprets benign environmental phenomena such as fog or clouds as wildfires, thereby triggering false alarms. While the paper does not instantiate them, other risks are disclosed as potential for this class of technology. For instance, the geographic bias noted above could potentially promote resource allocation inequality if lower model accuracy in certain regions led to delayed emergency response. Similarly, the use of GANs for data augmentation could degrade real-world performance if the synthetic data contains unrealistic artifacts, a risk strongly associated with threats to human safety and potential economic loss in a live deployment scenario.\n\nThe paper appears to make some effort to address the risk of incorrect predictions, though the grounding for these mitigations is inferred. Tentatively, the use of diverse environmental distractor datasets, such as images of fog and clouds, is a step toward inhibiting false positives. Likewise, the addition of specific architectural modifications to the object detector, such as SE blocks and CIoU loss, seems aimed at improving the model's ability to distinguish true wildfires from complex backgrounds. In summary, this audit identifies two moderately-grounded risks as actually instantiated by this paper—geographic representation bias and incorrect predictions from false alarms—while the more severe downstream societal impacts remain disclosures of category-level risk. The paper's attempts at mitigation are noted but are based on tentative inference rather than explicit statements from the authors.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (Geographically concentrated training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (Geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When a model trained on datasets from specific regions (e.g., South Korea, California, Croatia) is deployed in unrepresented ecosystems with different vegetation and environmental conditions.)\n- (Geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (Resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When lower model accuracy in underrepresented regions leads to delayed or missed wildfire detections, resulting in an unequal distribution of public safety protection.)\n- (Generative Adversarial Network Data Augmentation (GAN DA):TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (Prediction of incorrect results in high-risk GRS applications:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: If the GANs generate synthetic flame and smoke with unrealistic artifacts or systematic flaws, it can corrupt the training dataset and degrade the detector's real-world performance.)\n- (Prediction of incorrect results in high-risk GRS applications:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (Threats to human safety in emergency situations:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When a false negative (missed fire) occurs in a live monitoring system, delaying the dispatch of emergency services to a developing wildfire.)\n- (Automated real-time wildfire detection:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (Prediction of incorrect results in high-risk GRS applications:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When the model misinterprets benign environmental phenomena (e.g., fog, clouds, sunsets) as wildfires, triggering false alarms.)\n- (Prediction of incorrect results in high-risk GRS applications:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (Economic loss from misinformation-driven planning:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When false alarms lead to the unnecessary and costly deployment of finite emergency services, potentially diverting them from real incidents.)\n- (Use of diverse environmental distractor datasets:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (Prediction of incorrect results in high-risk GRS applications:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: By training the model on images of non-fire phenomena that can be confused with wildfires, such as fog, clouds, and sunsets.)\n- (Addition of SE blocks and CIoU loss to object detector:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (Prediction of incorrect results in high-risk GRS applications:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: By improving the model's ability to focus on relevant visual features and accurately localize small or indistinct objects like early-stage smoke.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: Geographically concentrated training data, Generative Adversarial Network Data Augmentation (GAN DA), Automated real-time wildfire detection\n  RiskMechanism: Geographic representation bias, Prediction of incorrect results in high-risk GRS applications\n  EthicalImpact: Resource allocation inequality, Threats to human safety in emergency situations, Economic loss from misinformation-driven planning\n  Mitigation: Use of diverse environmental distractor datasets, Addition of SE blocks and CIoU loss to object detector",
