   "id": "072",
   "source": {
    "title": "Deep learning in multimodal remote sensing data fusion: A comprehensive review",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2022.102926",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2022.102926",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2022",
    "abstract": "With the extremely rapid advances in remote sensing (RS) technology, a great quantity of Earth observation (EO) data featuring considerable and complicated heterogeneity are readily available nowadays, which renders researchers an opportunity to tackle current geoscience applications in a fresh way. With the joint utilization of EO data, much research on multimodal RS data fusion has made tremendous progress in recent years, yet these developed traditional algorithms inevitably meet the performance bottleneck due to the lack of the ability to comprehensively analyze and interpret strongly heterogeneous data. Hence, this non-negligible limitation further arouses an intense demand for an alternative tool with powerful processing competence. Deep learning (DL), as a cutting-edge technology, has witnessed remarkable breakthroughs in numerous computer vision tasks owing to its impressive ability in data representation and reconstruction. Naturally, it has been successfully applied to the field of multimodal RS data fusion, yielding great improvement compared with traditional methods. This survey aims to present a systematic overview in DL-based multimodal RS data fusion. More specifically, some essential knowledge about this topic is first given. Subsequently, a literature survey is conducted to analyze the trends of this field. Some prevalent sub-fields in the multimodal RS data fusion are then reviewed in terms of the to-be-fused data modalities, i.e., spatiospectral, spatiotemp"
   },
   "report": "This paper surveys the landscape of multimodal data fusion in remote sensing, focusing on deep learning techniques. The primary points of contact with ethical considerations arise from the specific types of data and models included in its scope. These triggers include the fusion of remote sensing imagery with human mobility data like GPS trajectories, the documented geographic concentration of the literature used to develop these models, and the prevalent use of deep neural networks (DNNs), which are often characterized by their black-box nature.\n\nThe audit's analysis reveals several instantiated risks at the mechanism level, alongside potential downstream impacts. A tentative finding, inferred from the paper's scope, is that the fusion of remote sensing with human mobility data, when integrating sources like taxi trajectories, promotes the disclosure of sensitive geospatial data. A more direct finding, based on the paper's own analysis, is that the unrepresentative geographic training data, with over 50% of surveyed literature originating from a single country, instantiates a risk of population bias. Furthermore, the paper's coverage of deep learning models like CNNs directly triggers a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, a risk mechanism conditioned on the non-interpretable nature of these methods. While these risks are instantiated, their potential impacts are not. The disclosure of sensitive data could lead to location privacy violations if used to expose homes and workspaces, and population bias could promote resource allocation inequality if deployed in underrepresented regions. Similarly, the lack of transparency could pose safety risks in critical missions like hazard monitoring. However, these impacts are disclosures of general risk for this class of technology, as this specific paper does not perform the actions that would trigger them.\n\nIn summary, the auditor finds three ethical risks instantiated by the paper's contribution, primarily at the level of risk mechanism rather than concrete harm. These findings are grounded with weak to moderate confidence. The analysis did not identify any specific mitigations proposed or implemented within the reviewed material. The more severe ethical impacts, including privacy violations and safety risks, remain potential disclosures associated with this category of methods rather than audit findings directly realized by this paper's work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (Fusion of remote sensing and human mobility data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (disclosure of sensitive geospatial data:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When integrating crowdsourced or sensor-derived geospatial big data (GBD) such as taxi trajectories and user logs into fusion models.)\n- (disclosure of sensitive geospatial data:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (location privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When exposing home locations, workspaces, and daily trajectories through the analysis of mobility patterns.)\n- (unrepresentative geographic training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When the literature and datasets used to develop models are geographically concentrated.)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When models trained on geographically biased data are applied to resource allocation tasks in underrepresented regions.)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When the surveyed fusion methods (CNNs, GANs, Transformers) lack inherent physical interpretability.)\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When opaque models are used in high-risk remote sensing applications like hazard monitoring.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: Fusion of remote sensing and human mobility data, unrepresentative geographic training data, black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: disclosure of sensitive geospatial data, population bias, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: location privacy violation, resource allocation inequality, safety risks in critical missions",
