   "source": {
    "title": "Semi-supervised water tank detection to support vector control of emerging infectious diseases transmitted by Aedes Aegypti",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2023.103304",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2023.103304",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "The disease transmitting mosquito Aedes Aegypti is an increasing global threat. It breeds in small artificial containers such as rainwater tanks and can be characterized by a short flight range. The resulting high spatial variability of abundance is challenging to model. Therefore, we tested an approach to map water tank density as a spatial proxy for urban Aedes Aegypti habitat suitability. Water tank density mapping was performed by a semi-supervised self-training approach based on open accessible satellite imagery for the city of Rio de Janeiro. We ran a negative binomial generalized linear regression model to evaluate the statistical significance of water tank density for modeling inner-urban Aedes Aegypti distribution measured by an entomological surveillance system between January 2019 and December 2021. Our proposed semi-supervised model outperformed a supervised model for water tank detection with respect to the F1-score by 22%. Water tank density was a significant predictor for the mean eggs per trap rate of Aedes Aegypti. This shows the potential of the proposed indicator to enrich urban entomological surveillance systems to plan more targeted vector control interventions, presumably leading to less infectious rates of dengue, Zika, and chikungunya in the future."
   },
   "report": "This audit examines a paper focused on AI-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data. The specific application involves identifying and mapping the density of household water tanks in Rio de Janeiro, using open-access satellite imagery. The ethical scope of this work is engaged through its technical approach of classifying features on private residential property and its stated goal of using this analysis to guide the deployment of public health resources, thereby linking a technical classification task directly to societal resource allocation.\n\nThe audit's findings indicate that the paper's methodology instantiates several ethical risks. With moderate confidence, the auditor finds that the technique of detecting objects like water tanks located in private backyards and on rooftops promotes a violation of location privacy. Furthermore, the analysis suggests a plausible causal pathway toward allocative harm. The paper's method of identifying specific infrastructure types within a complex urban landscape introduces a risk of misclassification of heterogeneous roof types, a mechanism the authors acknowledge through examples of false positives on visually similar objects like swimming pools or sunshades. This risk becomes ethically salient when, as is the case here, the roof typology is used as a proxy for socio-economic status to inform humanitarian aid. The model’s potential inaccuracies could therefore promote discriminatory resource allocation, channeling limited public health interventions based on a flawed proxy.\n\nIn terms of mitigation, the paper does appear to address the potential for systematic discrimination arising from biased social and crowdsourced datasets. By opting instead to manually label a balanced training set with samples from both favelas and standard residential areas, the authors avoid a common source of data-induced bias. Nevertheless, this audit identifies three ethical risks as actually instantiated by the paper's contribution, all with moderate confidence. These findings include a direct privacy concern and a more complex risk of discriminatory impact, rooted in the connection between a technical classification mechanism and its real-world application in resource allocation.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (location privacy violation:EthicalImpact) [PrivacyViolation]  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types)\n- (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When roof typology is used as a proxy for socio-economic status)\n- (biased social and crowdsourced datasets:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (systematic discrimination:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>  (when: When used in urban planning applications)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data, biased social and crowdsourced datasets\n  RiskMechanism: misclassification of heterogeneous roof types\n  EthicalImpact: location privacy violation, discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid, systematic discrimination",
