   "source": {
    "title": "A wavelet-artificial intelligence fusion approach (WAIFA) for blending Landsat and MODIS surface temperature",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2015.08.015",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2015.08.015",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2015",
    "abstract": "Land surface temperature (LST) is one of the key parameters in the physics of earth surface processes from local to global scales. However, thermal infrared (TIR) images at both high temporal and spatial resolutions are limited because of the technical limitations of current thermal sensors. Therefore, development of fusion models to obtain thermal data in high spatial and temporal resolutions is crucial in environmental studies. This paper presents a hybrid wavelet-artificial intelligence fusion approach (WAIFA)to produce LST data at the spatial resolution of Landsat 8 thermal bands. The theoretical basis and the application procedures of the proposed data fusion approach are explained. A case study was performed to predict LSTs of six dates in 2014 from March to August in East Azerbaijan Province, Iran. This approach uses powerful non-linear artificial intelligence modeling systems which can cope with the non-linear nature of the land surface temperature data. In addition, multi-spectral bands and different spectral indices are used as well as thermal data in the modeling process to consider the mixture properties of MODIS pixels. Using a 2D wavelet transform to capture the properties of the main signals (original bands) in horizontal, vertical, and diagonal directions to consider the effect of neighboring pixels is the other improvement of this modeling approach. It can also help the model to deal with the non-stationary properties of the satellite and land surface tempera"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a Wavelet-Artificial Intelligence Fusion Approach (WAIFA) that leverages powerful non-linear models, including Support Vector Regression (SVR), Adaptive Neuro-Fuzzy Inference Systems (ANFIS), and Artificial Neural Networks (ANN), to handle the non-linear nature of land surface temperature data. The primary ethical touchpoint for this work stems directly from this choice of methodology. The use of complex, non-linear artificial intelligence systems is the technical feature that triggers the subsequent ethical considerations regarding the model's interpretability and potential downstream consequences.\n\nBased on the methods employed, this audit identifies one instantiated risk. The use of non-linear models plausibly promotes algorithmic opacity, a finding supported with moderate confidence. This risk is conditional on the model's complex operations obscuring the reasoning behind its predictions, a common characteristic of the selected techniques. This opacity, in turn, is associated with a potential for downstream economic loss through the misallocation of public resources. However, this latter impact is only a disclosure of a category-level risk and is not instantiated by this paper. The risk of misallocation would only be triggered when model predictions, which the paper notes have inherent errors varying from 0.47K to 1.93K, are deployed for consequential environmental and agricultural resource management without sufficient explanation for those errors, an action not taken within the scope of this work.\n\nIn summary, this audit finds one risk actually instantiated by the paper's contribution and one disclosed risk associated with the general technique. The instantiated finding is that the WAIFA method plausibly introduces algorithmic opacity, a conclusion grounded with moderate confidence. No specific mitigations for this opacity were identified within the provided analysis. Therefore, the core finding relates to the interpretability of the model itself, while the more severe potential impact of misallocating resources remains a potential, but not triggered, concern for this class of model if deployed in a decision-making context.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (Wavelet-Artificial Intelligence Fusion Approach (WAIFA) using non-linear models (SVR, ANFIS, ANN):TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic opacity:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When the model's complex, non-linear operations obscure the reasoning behind its predictions.)\n- (algorithmic opacity:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (misallocation of public resources:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When model predictions with inherent, but unexplained, errors are used for consequential environmental and agricultural resource management.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: Wavelet-Artificial Intelligence Fusion Approach (WAIFA) using non-linear models (SVR, ANFIS, ANN)\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic opacity\n  EthicalImpact: misallocation of public resources",
