   "id": "078",
   "source": {
    "title": "Automated detection of rock glaciers using deep learning and object-based image analysis",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2020.112033",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2020.112033",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2020",
    "abstract": "Rock glaciers are an important component of the cryosphere and are one of the most visible manifestations of permafrost. While the significance of rock glacier contribution to streamflow remains uncertain, the contribution is likely to be important for certain parts of the world. High-resolution remote sensing data has permitted the creation of rock glacier inventories for large regions. However, due to the spectral similarity between rock glaciers and the surrounding material, the creation of such inventories is typically conducted based on manual interpretation, which is both time consuming and subjective. Here, we present a novel method that combines deep learning (convolutional neural networks or CNNs) and object-based image analysis (OBIA) into one workflow based on freely available Sentinel-2 optical imagery (10 m spatial resolution), Sentinel-1 interferometric coherence data, and a digital elevation model (DEM). CNNs identify recurring patterns and textures and produce a prediction raster, or heatmap where each pixel indicates the probability that it belongs to a certain class (i.e. rock glacier) or not. By using OBIA we can segment the datasets and classify objects based on their heatmap value as well as morphological and spatial characteristics. We analysed two distinct catchments, the La Laguna catchment in the Chilean semi-arid Andes and the Poiqu catchment in the central Himalaya. In total, our method mapped 108 of the 120 rock glaciers across both catchments with"
   },
   "report": "This paper employs convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for the automated mapping of geological landforms. The primary ethical consideration arises from the technical implementation of these CNNs, which can act as a trigger for risks associated with model performance. Specifically, the potential for the model to produce classification errors constitutes the main point of ethical contact, introducing a mechanism of inadvertent inferential error. The reliability of the automated maps generated by this technology is central to its ethical evaluation.\n\nBased on the evidence presented, this audit finds that the paper's method instantiates a risk of inadvertent inferential error. This finding is moderately grounded in the paper's own discussion of model performance. It is plausible that the CNN model promotes such errors under at least two conditions: first, when it confuses spectrally and texturally similar landforms, such as misidentifying debris flows as rock glaciers; and second, when it misclassifies stable landforms as geologic hazards due to their shared morphological profiles. While these inferential errors are instantiated, a more severe downstream impact remains a disclosure of potential risk. Specifically, this category of automated mapping could promote resource allocation inequality if flawed inventories were used for regional hydrological modeling and water resource planning, though this paper does not extend its methods to that application.\n\nThe paper's framing suggests an awareness of certain downstream harms. The potential for automated maps with unquantified errors to create safety risks in critical missions, particularly for geologic hazard assessments affecting mountain communities, is noted as not triggered by this work. In summary, the auditor finds two risks of inadvertent inferential error to be instantiated by the paper's methods, both supported by evidence of moderate confidence. A further societal impact concerning resource inequality is disclosed as a potential for this technology class but is not directly triggered by the paper's contribution.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (convolutional neural networks (cnns):TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When the model confuses spectrally and texturally similar landforms (e.g., rock glaciers vs. debris flows).)\n- (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When flawed inventories from automated mapping are used for regional hydrological modeling and water resource planning.)\n- (convolutional neural networks (cnns):TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When the model misclassifies stable landforms as geologic hazards, or vice-versa, due to shared morphological profiles.)\n- (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | n/a>  (when: When automated maps with unquantified errors are used for geologic hazard assessments threatening mountain communities.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: convolutional neural networks (cnns)\n  RiskMechanism: inadvertent inferential error\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, safety risks in critical missions",
