   "source": {
    "title": "Remote sensing of cyanobacteria-dominant algal blooms and water quality parameters in Zeekoevlei, a small hypertrophic lake, using MERIS",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2010.04.013",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2010.04.013",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2010",
    "abstract": "Eutrophication and cyanobacterial algal blooms present an increasing threat to the health of freshwater ecosystems and to humans who use these resources for drinking and recreation. Remote sensing is being used increasingly as a tool for monitoring these phenomena in inland and near-coastal waters. This study uses the Medium Resolution Imaging Spectrometer (MERIS) to view Zeekoevlei, a small hypertrophic freshwater lake situated on the Cape Flats in Cape Town, South Africa, dominated by Microcystis cyanobacteria. The lake's small size, highly turbid water, and covariant water constituents present a challenging case for both algorithm development and atmospheric correction. The objectives of the study are to assess the optical properties of the lake, to evaluate various atmospheric correction procedures, and to compare the performance of empirical and semi-analytical algorithms in hypertrophic water. In situ water quality parameter and radiometric measurements were made simultaneous to MERIS overpasses. Upwelling radiance measurements at depth 0.66m were corrected for instrument self-shading and processed to water-leaving reflectance using downwelling irradiance measurements and estimates of the vertical attenuation coefficient for upward radiance, K u, generated from a simple bio-optical model estimating the total absorption, a(λ), and backscattering coefficients, b b(λ). The normalised water-leaving reflectance was used for assessing the accuracy of image-based Dark Object S"
   },
   "report": "This paper develops and applies remote sensing models, specifically Neural Network algorithms and empirical regression models, for the purpose of monitoring water quality. The work engages with ethical considerations through its choice of modeling techniques and data sources. The primary ethical triggers identified are the use of Neural Network algorithms trained on non-local data for a geographically distinct application area, and the deployment of empirical models in an environment where water quality constituents are highly covariant.\n\nBased on the evidence presented, this audit finds two instantiated risks. First, the use of Neural Network algorithms trained on data from a different domain (e.g., European waters) than the application domain (a South African lake) plausibly promotes algorithmic bias. The paper itself notes that these non-local models failed to produce reasonable results, indicating a divergence between the training and application environments. Second, the paper's use of empirical regression models, under the specific condition of highly covariant water constituents, plausibly promotes a risk of misinterpretation by decision-makers. These models act more as general estimators of particulate loading rather than isolating individual constituents, which could lead to flawed conclusions if the nuance is lost. Beyond these findings, the audit notes potential downstream impacts that are not instantiated by this paper. Algorithmic bias, as a general mechanism, can promote resource allocation inequality when used for planning, and the misinterpretation of AI insights could potentially lead to public exposure to hazardous toxins if monitoring systems are used for public health decisions, though this latter connection is a more tentative inference.\n\nThe paper actively addresses some of the identified risks. An instantiated mitigation is present in the development and validation of regionally-tuned empirical algorithms using in-situ measurements, which directly inhibits the algorithmic bias resulting from non-local models. In summary, this audit identifies two moderately-grounded, instantiated risks concerning algorithmic bias and the potential for misinterpretation of model outputs. While the paper takes concrete steps to mitigate the bias, the risk of misinterpretation remains. The broader societal impacts of resource inequality and public harm are raised only as disclosures of category-level risk, not as findings directly triggered by this specific work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (Neural Network algorithms trained on non-local data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (Algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When training data domain (e.g., European waters) differs significantly from the application domain (e.g., a South African hypertrophic lake).)\n- (Algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (Resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When biased analytics are used to determine city-wide planning and service distribution.)\n- (Development of regionally-tuned empirical algorithms with in-situ validation:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (Algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: Implementation during AI development and deployment.)\n- (Empirical regression models for water quality:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (Misinterpretation of AI insights by decision-makers:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When water constituents are highly covariant.)\n- (Misinterpretation of AI insights by decision-makers:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (Public exposure to hazardous toxins:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <inferred | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When monitoring systems are used for public health and safety decisions.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: Neural Network algorithms trained on non-local data, Empirical regression models for water quality\n  RiskMechanism: Algorithmic bias, Misinterpretation of AI insights by decision-makers\n  EthicalImpact: Resource allocation inequality, Public exposure to hazardous toxins\n  Mitigation: Development of regionally-tuned empirical algorithms with in-situ validation",
