   "id": "081",
   "source": {
    "title": "Estimating leaf mass per area and equivalent water thickness based on leaf optical properties: Potential and limitations of physical modeling and machine learning",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2018.11.002",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2018.11.002",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2019",
    "abstract": "Leaf mass per area (LMA) and leaf equivalent water thickness (EWT) are key leaf functional traits providing information for many applications including ecosystem functioning modeling and fire risk management. In this paper, we investigate two common conclusions generally made for LMA and EWT estimation based on leaf optical properties in the near-infrared (NIR) and shortwave infrared (SWIR) domains: (1) physically-based approaches estimate EWT accurately and LMA poorly, while (2) statistically-based and machine learning (ML) methods provide accurate estimates of both LMA and EWT. Using six experimental datasets including broadleaf species samples of &gt;150 species collected over tropical, temperate and boreal ecosystems, we compared the performances of a physically-based method (PROSPECT model inversion) and a ML algorithm (support vector machine regression, SVM) to infer EWT and LMA based on leaf reflectance and transmittance. We assessed several merit functions to invert PROSPECT based on iterative optimization and investigated the spectral domain to be used for optimal estimation of LMA and EWT. We also tested several strategies to select the training samples used by the SVM, in order to investigate the generalization ability of the derived regression models. We evidenced that using spectral information from 1700 to 2400 nm leads to strong improvement in the estimation of EWT and LMA when performing a PROSPECT inversion, decreasing the LMA and EWT estimation errors by 55%"
   },
   "report": "This paper utilizes Support Vector Machine (SVM) Regression for applications in environmental science. The primary ethical considerations stem from the performance characteristics of this specific machine learning technique. The paper’s stated relevance to domains such as wildfire risk indexing and its testing on commercial timber stands situate the work in contexts where the reliability of predictive models has direct implications for safety and economic resource management.\n\nThe audit's central finding is that the paper’s methodology instantiates a risk of creating misleading machine learning models that yield incorrect predictions. This conclusion is supported with moderate confidence by the paper's own text, which notes that its \"SVM regression models demonstrate highly restricted generalization capabilities\" under the specific condition of being \"tested on fully independent datasets.\" This limited generalization is therefore an identified risk of the presented method. While the paper does not deploy its model in a way that directly causes downstream harm, this risk mechanism is linked to significant potential impacts. Such incorrect predictions could plausibly promote safety risks in critical missions if the model were used for safety-critical applications like wildfire risk assessment. Additionally, a weaker, inferred connection suggests that this unreliability could contribute to the mismanagement of agricultural and forestry resources if deployed for commercial yield estimation. It is important to clarify that these physical harm and economic loss impacts are presented here as disclosures of category-level risk, not as outcomes instantiated by this specific paper.\n\nThe provided materials did not indicate any specific mitigations implemented by the authors to address the identified generalization limitations of their models. In summary, this audit identifies one core technical risk as being actively instantiated by the paper's contribution, an assessment based on moderately strong evidence within the paper itself. The associated downstream harms are not instantiated but are disclosed as plausible concerns for any future real-world deployment of this technology, particularly in the safety-critical and commercial domains the paper references.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (Support Vector Machine (SVM) Regression:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When applied to fully independent datasets not used in training.)\n- (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When used for safety-critical applications like wildfire risk assessment.)\n- (Support Vector Machine (SVM) Regression:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When applied to fully independent datasets not used in training.)\n- (misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (mismanagement of agricultural and forestry resources:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <inferred | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When used for commercial resource management and yield estimation.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: Support Vector Machine (SVM) Regression\n  RiskMechanism: misleading machine learning models to yield incorrect predictions\n  EthicalImpact: safety risks in critical missions, mismanagement of agricultural and forestry resources",
