   "source": {
    "title": "SCARF: A new algorithm for continuous prediction of biomass dynamics using machine learning and Landsat time series",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2024.114348",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2024.114348",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2024",
    "abstract": "We developed the SCARF (Spatial Mismatch and Systematic Prediction Error Corrected cAscade Random Forests) algorithm for continuous prediction of biomass dynamics using machine learning and Landsat Time Series (LTS). Our approach addresses the challenges posed by the cloudy subtropical forests in southern China, where monitoring biomass dynamics is notoriously difficult. To derive spectral-temporal features from the LTS, we applied the Continuous Change Detection and Classification (CCDC) algorithm (Zhu and Woodcock, 2014). Subsequently, we employed the cascade random forests machine learning algorithm for biomass prediction. This new approach corrects the spatial mismatch effects between plots and Landsat pixels as well as the systematic prediction errors in the machine learning model. As a result, it substantially enhances biomass prediction accuracy, with a coefficient of determination (R2) of 0.83 and a root mean square error (RMSE) of 6.27 Mg ha-1. In comparison, the commonly used random forests approach yields an R2 of 0.47 and RMSE of 8.52 Mg ha-1. Additionally, it provides reliable spatial prediction beyond the model-training area, achieving an R2 of 0.79 and an RMSE of 6.62 Mg ha-1. Furthermore, we demonstrate that modeling five different forest age groups separately further improves prediction accuracies, resulting in an increased R2 of 0.87 and a reduced RMSE of 3.65 Mg ha-1. A comparison of the allometric model prediction from the field plots and those from the SC"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a high-complexity GeoAI model, specifically a cascade random forests algorithm, for the purpose of continuous biomass prediction. The primary ethical considerations arise from three aspects of its methodology. First, the paper's evaluation relies on non-spatially-explicit metrics such as the overall coefficient of determination (R2) and root mean square error (RMSE). Second, the contribution utilizes a complex machine learning model, which is characterized as a black-box system. Finally, the iterative and recursive nature of the algorithm constitutes a high-complexity model with potential computational costs. These characteristics serve as the primary triggers for the ethical risks examined in this audit.\n\nThe audit identifies three distinct risks as instantiated by the paper's methodology. The use of non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics represents a strong finding, as reporting only aggregate scores promotes an evaluation bias that can hide significant regional variability in model performance. Additionally, two moderately plausible findings were identified: the model's nature as a black-box deep neural network promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, and its high complexity promotes greenhouse gas emissions from the computational resources required. Beyond these instantiated findings, this class of model carries potential downstream risks that are not directly triggered by this paper but warrant disclosure. For example, evaluation bias can lead to reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions when such models are deployed, and a lack of transparency could introduce safety risks in critical high-risk applications. Similarly, while the model generates emissions, the broader impact on climate change affecting vulnerable populations remains a potential, conditional consequence of the technology class at a global scale.\n\nThe paper does not appear to implement specific mitigations for the identified risks. The risk of evaluation bias, for instance, could be addressed by incorporating spatially-explicit performance evaluation to expose where the model is biased, though this was not performed. In summary, this audit identifies three instantiated risks: one strongly grounded finding related to evaluation bias from aggregate metrics, and two moderately grounded findings concerning algorithmic transparency and computational emissions. The more severe downstream societal impacts remain potential disclosures for this category of research rather than direct findings against this specific work, as the conditions for their instantiation were not met.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When performance is only measured as an aggregate overall score on a corpus)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of geoparsers for downstream geospatial tasks)\n- (spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: By exposing where a geoparser is biased towards or against)\n- (opaque ai systems:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misinterpretation of ai insights by decision-makers:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When used by non-technical stakeholders or policymakers)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n- (High-complexity GeoAI models:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (greenhouse gas emissions:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (greenhouse gas emissions:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (climate change consequences affecting vulnerable populations:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Global scope affecting communities most vulnerable to climate change)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score, opaque ai systems, black-box nature of deep neural networks, High-complexity GeoAI models\n  RiskMechanism: evaluation bias hiding regional variability, misinterpretation of ai insights by decision-makers, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, greenhouse gas emissions\n  EthicalImpact: reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions, safety risks in critical missions, climate change consequences affecting vulnerable populations\n  Mitigation: spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection",
