   "id": "084",
   "source": {
    "title": "Towards global long-term water transparency products from the Landsat archive",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2023.113889",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2023.113889",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Secchi Disk Depth (Zsd) is one of the most fundamental and widely used water-quality indicators quantifiable via optical remote sensing. Despite decades of research, development, and demonstrations, currently, there is no operational model that enables the retrieval of Zsd from the rich archive of Landsat, the long-standing civilian Earth-observation program (1972 – present). Devising a robust Zsd model requires a comprehensive in situ dataset for testing and validation, enabling consistent mapping across optically varying global aquatic ecosystems. This study utilizes Mixture Density Networks (MDNs) trained with a large in situ dataset (N = 5689) from 300+ water bodies to formulate and implement a global Zsd algorithm for Landsat sensors, including the Thematic Mapper (TM), Enhanced Thematic Mapper Plus (ETM+), and Operational Land Imager (OLI) aboard Landsat-5, -7, -8, and -9, respectively. Through an extensive Monte Carlo cross-validation with in situ data, we showed that MDNs improved Zsd retrieval when compared to other commonly used machine-learning (ML) models and recently developed semi-analytical algorithms, achieving a median symmetric accuracy (ε) of ∼29% and median bias (β) of ∼3%). A fully trained MDN model was then applied to atmospherically corrected Landsat data (i.e., remote sensing reflectance; Rrs) to both further validate our MDN-estimated Zsd products using an independent global satellite-to-in situ matchup dataset (N = 3534) and to demonstrate their util"
   },
   "report": "This audit assesses a paper that develops a global water clarity retrieval model using Mixture Density Networks (MDNs) on Landsat satellite imagery. The work's ethical dimensions arise from its technical approach—specifically, its use of a global model trained across different sensor generations—and its stated goal of making water quality monitoring accessible to non-technical stakeholders like citizen scientists and local policymakers. These aspects trigger considerations of model bias and the potential for misinterpretation of complex AI-driven environmental insights.\n\nThe primary audit finding concerns a risk of bias that is instantiated by the paper's own methodology. The auditor finds it plausible that the global Zsd retrieval model promotes bias, specifically under the condition that it is applied across different sensor generations which possess varying instrument calibration and atmospheric correction uncertainties. This finding is directly supported by the authors' observation of higher errors and biases for older Landsat sensors (TM and ETM+). While the paper's model creates this bias, the subsequent risk of misinterpretation or misuse of this data by decision-makers is not instantiated by the paper itself. However, it is a relevant disclosure that biased environmental data, if relied upon without local expertise, can lead to negative impacts such as economic loss. Similarly, while the authors' goal of broader access is laudable, the use of complex Mixture Density Networks by non-technical stakeholders presents a potential for misinterpretation of AI insights, a category-level risk that is not triggered in the current study but is relevant to its proposed deployment.\n\nIn terms of mitigation, there is tentative evidence that the paper takes steps to address model performance issues, which indirectly inhibits the identified bias. The authors implement a structured evaluation framework with quantifiable metrics, including a partition-based data splitting strategy to avoid accuracy inflation from spatio-temporal autocorrelation. This can be interpreted as a partial mitigation against bias, though its grounding is weak as it is not explicitly framed as an ethical safeguard by the authors. In summary, this audit identifies one moderately-grounded risk of data bias that is instantiated by the paper's method. This is accompanied by two disclosures of potential downstream risks that the paper does not trigger, and one weakly-grounded mitigation that is present in the paper's evaluation design.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (global zsd retrieval model from landsat:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When applied across sensor generations with varying instrument calibration and atmospheric correction uncertainties.)\n- (bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: Overreliance on AI results without local expertise)\n- (structured evaluation framework and quantifiable metrics:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (bias:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: Implementation during AI development and deployment)\n- (mixture density networks (mdns):TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misinterpretation of ai insights by decision-makers:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When used by non-technical stakeholders or policymakers)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: global zsd retrieval model from landsat, mixture density networks (mdns)\n  RiskMechanism: bias, misinterpretation of ai insights by decision-makers\n  EthicalImpact: misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data\n  Mitigation: structured evaluation framework and quantifiable metrics",
