   "id": "086",
   "source": {
    "title": "A flexible and efficient knowledge-guided machine learning data assimilation (KGML-DA) framework for agroecosystem prediction in the US Midwest",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2023.113880",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2023.113880",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "Process-based models are widely used to predict the agroecosystem dynamics, but such modeled results often contain considerable uncertainty due to the imperfect model structure, biased model parameters, and inaccurate or inaccessible model inputs. Data assimilation (DA) techniques are widely adopted to reduce prediction uncertainty by calibrating model parameters or dynamically updating the model state variables using observations. However, high computational cost, difficulties in mitigating model structural error, and low flexibility in framework development hinder its applications in large-scale agroecosystem predictions. In this study, we addressed these challenges by proposing a novel DA framework that integrates a Knowledge-Guided Machine Learning (KGML)-based surrogate with tensorized ensemble Kalman filter (EnKF) and parallelized particle swarm optimization (PSO) to effectively assimilate historical and in-season multi-source remote sensing data. Specifically, we incorporate knowledge from a process-based model, ecosys, into a Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU)-based hierarchical neural network. The hierarchical architecture of KGML-DA mimics key processes of ecosys and builds a causal relationship between target variables. Using carbon budget quantification in the US Corn-Belt as a context, we evaluated KGML-DA's performance in predicting key processes of the carbon cycle at three agricultural sites (US-Ne1, US-Ne2, US-Ne3), along with county-level (627 counties) and 30-m pix"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a GRU-based hierarchical neural network for high-resolution agroecosystem prediction and risk assessment. The ethical dimensions of this work are triggered primarily by the model's training data, which is sampled from a specific geographic area, and by its potential applications in domains such as crop insurance assessment and agricultural resource management. The paper also touches upon ethical considerations through its explicit focus on creating a computationally efficient surrogate model, which has implications for environmental impact.\n\nThe auditor's primary finding is a moderately-grounded risk of algorithmic bias being instantiated by the paper's methodology. This risk arises because the model is trained on data sampled exclusively from the U.S. Corn Belt, which may not be representative of all conditions in the broader application domain, potentially leading to biased performance in other agricultural regions. While this risk of bias is instantiated, its potential downstream impact—resource allocation inequality—is not. The paper notes the model could be used for optimizing irrigation or fertilizer application; should a biased model be used for such planning, it could lead to unequal distributions, but this remains a potential disclosure as the paper does not implement this resource allocation step. Similarly, the paper's general capability for risk assessment belongs to a class of AI models that, when applied to crop insurance, could promote individual risk profiling and subsequent economic loss from increased costs. However, this paper does not apply its model to insurance rate setting, so this remains a disclosure of a potential risk, not an instantiated finding.\n\nIn terms of mitigation, the paper's development of a computationally efficient surrogate model is found to actively inhibit the environmental impact associated with large-scale, high-performance computing. By prioritizing computational efficiency, the authors directly address and neutralize a common risk in large AI model development. In summary, this audit identifies one instantiated risk—algorithmic bias, based on moderately confident evidence—while noting that its more severe potential impacts are not triggered by this work. Other potential risks related to insurance applications are raised only as disclosures about the technology class. The paper is also found to have proactively mitigated the environmental harm of its computational methods.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (AI models for agroecosystem prediction and risk assessment:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (individual risk profiling based on location and driving data:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When applied to crop insurance rate setting)\n- (individual risk profiling based on location and driving data:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (economic loss from increased insurance costs:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When inaccurate or biased risk profiles are used to set insurance premiums.)\n- (GRU-based hierarchical neural network for agroecosystem modeling:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When training data is not representative of all conditions in the application domain.)\n- (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When biased analytics are used to determine agricultural planning and service distribution.)\n- (Computationally efficient surrogate modeling:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (environmental impact:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When prioritizing computational efficiency over raw power)\n- (environmental impact:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (environmental degradation and threat to future human life:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | n/a>  (when: When resource use threatens long-term environmental sustainability and human life)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: AI models for agroecosystem prediction and risk assessment, GRU-based hierarchical neural network for agroecosystem modeling\n  RiskMechanism: individual risk profiling based on location and driving data, algorithmic bias, environmental impact\n  EthicalImpact: economic loss from increased insurance costs, resource allocation inequality, environmental degradation and threat to future human life\n  Mitigation: Computationally efficient surrogate modeling",
