   "id": "087",
   "source": {
    "title": "Influence of data and methods on high-resolution imagery-based tree species recognition considering phenology: The case of temperate forests",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2025.114654",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2025.114654",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Seasonal phenological transformations alter tree appearances, notably by influencing the size and color of the foliage. It has long been anticipated that such phenology induced characteristics can help address the tree-species recognition problem, a fundamental challenge in forest science. Yet, studies on tree-species recognition using remote sensing and phenological characteristics have been rare, due to the very limited availability of high spatiotemporal resolution observations. Moreover, the interactions between the effectiveness of phenological characteristics, remote sensing data, and the analytical methodologies have not yet been sufficiently explored. The understanding of how to integrate multi-temporal observations and phenological characteristics in tree-species recognition has been lacking. This study aims to identify principles for optimizing species recognition by combining data, methods, and phenological dynamics. This involves understanding the impact factors of various methodologies, and how they interact with phenological characteristics and datasets at different times and/or frequencies. The study was carried out using multi-temporal high-resolution optical images of a temperate forest, which were collected in 2021 during leaf growth and senescence periods between May and October, i.e., three leaf growth (May–August) and three leaf senescence (September–October) periods. The test site comprised 14 different tree classes, including 11 species, 2 genera, and 1"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a technical contribution employing Deep Learning Methodologies for the purpose of tree species recognition. The primary intersection with ethical considerations occurs in the model development stage, specifically related to the composition of the training data. The use of a deep learning approach in this context serves as the trigger for potential biases, particularly when the data contains imbalances across the different categories the model is designed to identify.\n\nThe auditor finds that the paper's methodology instantiates a risk of algorithmic bias. This finding is supported with moderate confidence, as the paper itself notes that \"the current main limitations in the tree species recognition lie in sample imbalance as the targeted species number increases.\" This directly suggests that the method promotes algorithmic bias under the condition of imbalanced training data, which the paper appears to encounter. While this form of bias belongs to a class of risks that can lead to downstream impacts such as resource allocation inequality and economic loss, this remains a potential disclosure for this work. That more severe impact is conditional upon the use of these biased analytics to inform conservation and forest management, an application which this paper does not instantiate.\n\nBased on the provided information, the paper does not appear to present specific mitigations for the identified risk of bias stemming from data imbalance. In summary, this audit identifies one instantiated ethical risk mechanism—algorithmic bias—which is a moderately grounded finding based on the paper's own text. A more severe potential harm, resource allocation inequality, is disclosed as a category-level risk associated with this type of analysis but is not triggered by the paper's direct contribution.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (Deep Learning Methodologies:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When training data contains sample imbalances for specific species types.)\n- (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When biased analytics are used to inform conservation and forest management.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: Deep Learning Methodologies\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic bias\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality",
