   "source": {
    "title": "Understanding the robustness of spectral-temporal metrics across the global Landsat archive from 1984 to 2019 – a quantitative evaluation",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2023.113823",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2023.113823",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2023",
    "abstract": "The Landsat archive is one of the richest Earth observation datasets available and provides long-term data at fairly high temporal and spatial resolution globally. Temporal aggregation is frequently used to condense single observations into a more digestible feature space that provides spatially gap-free data to fulfill demands of many processing strategies that rely on homogeneous data coverage across a large area, e.g., machine learning-based land cover classification. Spectral Temporal Metrics (STMs) represent a conceptually simple feature space wherein multiple observations are temporally aggregated by statistical functions. The quality and inter-annual consistency of STMs is affected by data availability, including usable clear-sky observations that vary in time and space due to satellite lifecycles, sensor failures, changes of observation modes, climate regimes, orbital overlaps, as well as inter-annual variability of cloud cover. However, the relationship between data availability and STM consistency between years is still poorly understood, especially as differences in STMs between years can both result from inter-annual variability in data availability, as well as inter-annual variability of land surfaces. In this study, we systematically quantify the effect of inter-annual data availability on annual STMs for the years 1984–2019, while completely controlling for inter-annual land surface changes. Our results are expected to help assess where on Earth, and in what pe"
   },
   "report": "This paper's technical contribution involves the use of deep learning models to analyze satellite data, with a specific focus on the challenges posed by geographic data scarcity in rural and remote areas. The work touches upon ethical considerations through its direct engagement with how spatially and temporally variable data availability—driven by factors like cloud cover and sensor lifecycles—can impact the reliability of models used for large-scale mapping and monitoring. The primary ethical triggers arise from the potential for these data gaps to introduce systematic biases into analytical outputs.\n\nThe auditor's analysis reveals several causal risk pathways. Based on the paper's methods, there is a plausible finding that geographic data scarcity promotes a population estimation bias, especially when datasets fail to adequately represent target regions like equatorial Africa due to persistent cloud cover. With moderate confidence, this audit finds that such a bias, in the context of global environmental monitoring, can in turn lead to inequitable resource allocation from misclassification. Furthermore, the paper's use of deep learning models under these conditions of heterogeneous data availability appears to promote an evaluation bias that hides regional variability in model performance. It should be disclosed that this type of evaluation mechanism belongs to a class of methods that can potentially reduce reliability and fairness in underserved regions, though this paper does not instantiate that specific downstream impact.\n\nThe paper does, however, incorporate a key mitigation. The analysis shows that the authors employ uncertainty quantification to assess the reliability of their temporal metrics before they are used in downstream models, a technique which serves to inhibit the identified risk of population estimation bias. In summary, this audit identifies four instantiated risks related to data scarcity, model evaluation, and equitable outcomes, all of which are moderately grounded. These findings are partially addressed by an instantiated mitigation strategy. The primary concerns therefore remain at the level of audit findings, supplemented by one disclosure of a related, but not triggered, category-level risk.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (geographic data scarcity in rural and remote areas:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When datasets fail to represent actual target regions due to spatially and temporally variable cloud cover, seasonal gaps (e.g., snow), or sensor lifecycle events.)\n- (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable resource allocation from misclassification:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management, such as global environmental monitoring.)\n- (uncertainty quantification:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (population estimation bias:RiskMechanism)  <inferred | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When applied to assess the reliability of temporal metrics before their use in downstream models.)\n- (deep learning models for population mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: Under conditions of spatial heterogeneity in data availability driven by different climate regimes.)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of GeoAI models for downstream geospatial tasks like environmental monitoring or agricultural policy.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: geographic data scarcity in rural and remote areas, deep learning models for population mapping\n  RiskMechanism: population estimation bias, evaluation bias hiding regional variability\n  EthicalImpact: inequitable resource allocation from misclassification, reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions\n  Mitigation: uncertainty quantification",
