   "id": "089",
   "source": {
    "title": "A more precise retrieval of sun-induced chlorophyll fluorescence from satellite data using artificial neural networks",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2025.114987",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2025.114987",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "In recent years, sun-induced chlorophyll fluorescence (SIF) retrieved from satellite platforms has been demonstrated to be a good proxy of gross primary production (GPP). However, existing data-driven methods based on singular value decomposition (SVD) commonly lead to high retrieval noise for single SIF observations, given the fact that SIF often has a low signal-to-noise ratio. Spatial and/or temporal aggregation has typically been used to reduce these noises. Such aggregation may diminish the effective spatial and/or temporal resolutions of current SIF products but potentially exacerbate uncertainty in interpreting SIF data. To address this issue, this study proposes a more precise data-driven method for retrieving SIF using an artificial neural network (ANN), which was trained using spatially aggregated SIF as the response variable and radiance in the spectral region of 743–758 nm as the explanatory variable. The feasibility of the ANN-based SIF retrieval method was first demonstrated using model simulations based on SCOPE and MODTRAN. Then, the ANN models were trained using OCO-2/3 SIF and TROPOMI radiance after careful matching of the overpass time and “sun-target-viewing” geometry. OCO-2/3 SIF, retrieved using high-spectral-resolution data within a narrow spectral window, is considered accurate and OCO-2 SIF was further validated by airborne SIF measurements. The resulting ANN model led to a high retrieval accuracy for SIF with an R2 of 0.85 and an RMSE of 0.217 mW∙m−2"
   },
   "report": "This paper proposes a data-driven method using an Artificial Neural Network (ANN) to produce a global Solar-Induced Chlorophyll Fluorescence (SIF) product, intended to improve estimates of Gross Primary Production (GPP) for carbon accounting and climate policy. The primary ethical touchpoints identified in this audit relate to the technical features of the model's training data and its architecture. Specifically, the use of geographically concentrated ground-truth data for a model with a stated global application, and the selection of an ANN, a method known for its \"black-box\" nature, serve as triggers for the risks analyzed below.\n\nThis audit identifies two moderately-grounded risks as instantiated by the paper's methodology. It is a plausible finding that the use of unrepresentative geographic training data, which is concentrated in North America and hyper-arid regions of the Sahara and Arabian Peninsula, promotes a population bias in the resulting global model. Given the paper's stated application in the context of land use and resource management, such a bias could in turn promote resource allocation inequality when used to inform regional and national carbon offset monitoring. Separately, the paper's use of an ANN, which is described as a black-box model, directly instantiates a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability. While such opaque methods can introduce safety risks in high-risk remote sensing applications, this remains a potential disclosure for this class of technique rather than a risk found to be instantiated by this specific paper.\n\nThe provided analysis does not indicate any specific mitigations implemented by the authors to address the identified risks of population bias or the lack of algorithmic transparency. In summary, this audit finds two risks to be instantiated, both with moderate confidence: one concerning the potential for geographically biased data to lead to inequitable outcomes in climate policy, and another regarding the inherent lack of transparency in the selected ANN model. A further category-level risk related to safety is disclosed as a potential concern but is not found to be triggered by this work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (unrepresentative geographic training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When ground-truth validation data is geographically concentrated in a model intended for global application.)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n- (black-box nature of deep neural networks:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: high-risk remote sensing applications)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: unrepresentative geographic training data, black-box nature of deep neural networks\n  RiskMechanism: population bias, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, safety risks in critical missions",
