   "id": "091",
   "source": {
    "title": "Built-up area mapping in China from GF-3 SAR imagery based on the framework of deep learning",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2021.112515",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2021.112515",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2021",
    "abstract": "Timely and reliable acquisition of built-up areas (BAs) information in large regions is of great significance for the assessment of the influence of human activities in local, regional and even global environments and promotes the sustainable development of cities. In this study, a deep learning based framework is presented to automatically extract BAs from Gaofen-3 (GF-3) data in China. In the framework, a U-Net structure based deep learning with convolutional neural network is implemented for semantic segmentation to extract BAs. To overcome the problem of network degradation when the neural network layers become deeper, residual blocks were introduced via identity shortcut connections to add to U-Net. About 30,000 samples containing different distribution types of BAs and corresponding labeled binary images, which are from 27 scenes of GF-3 SAR images covering different regions (for example plain, hilly and mountainous regions) in China, were obtained for model training. With the trained model, more than 1700 scenes of 10-m resolution GF-3 Fine Stripmap II (FSII) mode single-polarized images covering the whole country of China were processed to obtain the BA map of China. On the one hand, quality evaluation based on the confusion matrix was performed to determine the accuracy of the results with the ground truth data, which were manually interpreted by experts. The experimental results show that among 34 provinces or regions, the overall accuracy ranges from 76.05% to 93.4"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a deep-learning algorithm for image segmentation, focusing on AI-driven building detection from remote sensing data. The primary point of contact with ethical considerations arises from the application of this algorithm across diverse geographical areas, which serves as a trigger for evaluating performance disparities. The model's demonstrated variability in accuracy across these different contexts forms the basis for this ethical audit.\n\nThe analysis reveals one instantiated risk finding and several related disclosures. This audit finds, with moderate confidence, that the deep-learning algorithm promotes algorithmic bias. This finding is grounded in the paper's own results, which show that the model's performance varies systematically across different geomorphological regions; for example, lower accuracies are reported in arid and mountainous Western regions where environmental features like exposed rocks and dry soils are spectrally similar to buildings. While this paper does not implement downstream applications, this class of technology is associated with potential harms. If such biased analytics were used to determine city-wide planning, they could promote resource allocation inequality. Likewise, the underlying risk mechanism of misclassifying buildings, particularly when training data has sample imbalances, could lead to discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid scenarios where building detection is a proxy for distributing assistance. These latter harms, however, are only potential disclosures, as they are not triggered by the paper's specific contribution.\n\nThe audit did not identify any explicit mitigations presented in the paper for the identified risk. In summary, this audit surfaces one instantiated ethical risk—algorithmic bias due to geographical performance variance—which is supported with moderate confidence. The other potential impacts on resource allocation and humanitarian aid remain disclosures of category-level risks rather than direct findings against this work. The core finding is the performance disparity itself, which should be a key consideration before any operational deployment of the model.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (deep-learning algorithm for image segmentation beam:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When model performance varies systematically across different geomorphological regions.)\n- (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When biased analytics are used to determine city-wide planning and service distribution.)\n- (ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When training data contains sample imbalances for specific infrastructure types or background materials.)\n- (misclassification of heterogeneous roof types:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When building presence is used as a proxy for allocating resources to populations.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: deep-learning algorithm for image segmentation beam, ai-driven building detection and classification from remote sensing data\n  RiskMechanism: algorithmic bias, misclassification of heterogeneous roof types\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, discriminatory resource allocation in humanitarian aid",
