   "id": "092",
   "source": {
    "title": "Mapping recreational marine traffic from Sentinel-2 imagery using YOLO object detection models",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2025.114791",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2025.114791",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Identifying where maritime activities take place, and quantifying their potential impact on marine biodiversity, is important for the sustainable management of marine areas, spatial planning and marine conservation. Detection and monitoring of small vessels, such as pleasure crafts, has been challenging due to limited data availability with adequate temporal and spatial resolution. Here, we develop an analysis framework to detect and quantify small vessels, using openly available Sentinel-2 optical imagery, and the YOLO-family object detection models. We also show how existing spatial datasets can be used to improve the quality of the model output. We chose five distinct marine areas along the Finnish coast in the northern Baltic Sea and manually annotated 8,768 vessels for training and validating object detection models. The top-performing model, based on F1-score, achieved a test set F1-score of 0.863 and an mAP50 of 0.888. This model was then used to quantify pleasure crafts in the southern part of Finland from May to September 2022, using all available Sentinel-2 images with sufficient image quality. Detected recreational traffic was primarily concentrated on boating lanes and close to marinas, with weekend traffic averaging approximately twice the volume of weekday traffic. The developed approach can be used to identify areas with high boat traffic, thus supporting sustainable spatial planning, ecological impact avoidance, and serving as an indicator of recreational popu"
   },
   "report": "This audit examines a paper that develops an analysis framework using YOLO-family object detection models to detect and quantify small vessels from openly available Sentinel-2 optical imagery. The work touches on ethical considerations through two primary technical features. First, it employs a form of black-box spatial analysis, which can obscure the reasoning behind its outputs. Second, the method is developed with a notable lack of geographic diversity in its training and evaluation corpora, being focused specifically on the Finnish coast, while the authors simultaneously propose that the approach is scalable for global application.\n\nThe analysis of this paper's methods reveals several instantiated ethical risks. The auditor finds that the use of complex, non-transparent object detection models for this task plausibly promotes inadvertent inferential error, a moderate-confidence finding that arises when processing complex geographic variables without transparent guardrails. Critically, these potential errors are then strongly linked to a risk of inequitable social outcomes, including economic loss. This connection is established because the paper's stated applications—informing sustainable spatial planning, ecological impact avoidance, and assessing recreational popularity—are high-stakes domains where errors could lead to unjust resource allocation or flawed environmental policy. Further, the model's training on a geographically narrow dataset (the Finnish coast) while being framed as globally scalable plausibly promotes geographic representation bias, another moderate-confidence finding. Separately, this audit makes one disclosure: techniques with such geographic representation bias can potentially promote an unequal quality of geoparsing services across different regions, though this specific impact is not instantiated by the paper itself.\n\nIn conclusion, this audit identifies three ethical risks as actually instantiated by the paper’s contribution, with no explicit mitigations noted in the analyzed material. The causal chain linking the use of black-box methods to inadvertent inferential error and subsequent inequitable social outcomes is the most significant finding, with the final impact being strongly grounded. The risk of geographic representation bias stemming from the limited training data is also instantiated, though this finding is moderately grounded. These findings stand in contrast to one disclosure of a potential category-level risk that this paper does not trigger. The paper, therefore, presents multiple, grounded ethical risks that warrant consideration, particularly given its intended application in real-world planning and environmental management.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (lack of geographic diversity in training and evaluation corpora:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When a model trained for a specific geography is claimed to be globally scalable.)\n- (geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (unequal quality of geoparsing services across geographic regions:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: Across global and local scales)\n- (black-box spatial analysis:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When complex multidimensional geographic variables are processed without transparent guardrails.)\n- (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable social outcomes:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: In the absence of ethical guides to provide checks and balances on data and methods.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: lack of geographic diversity in training and evaluation corpora, black-box spatial analysis\n  RiskMechanism: geographic representation bias, inadvertent inferential error\n  EthicalImpact: unequal quality of geoparsing services across geographic regions, inequitable social outcomes",
