   "id": "094",
   "source": {
    "title": "Assessing the accuracy of Sentinel-2 instantaneous subpixel shorelines using synchronous UAV ground truth surveys",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2022.113293",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2022.113293",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2022",
    "abstract": "Due to recent technological advancements in the field of cloud-based satellite remote sensing, the barriers to global analysis ready dataset access and processing have lowered drastically increasing the opportunity for large-scale long-term satellite-derived shoreline monitoring solutions. However, validation studies employing synchronous and independent in-situ instantaneous shorelines at scale are limited. Thanks to a unique dataset of 47 synchronous UAV photogrammetric surveys in 15 coastal locations in Victoria, Australia, over 3 years, we validated Sentinel-2 instantaneous subpixel shorelines extracted using the most common water indices, CoastSat and a tidal-balanced convolutional neural network (Unet+++). We assessed the accuracy of the water level estimation using 9 wave run-up models and wave data sourced from a nearshore wave buoy network, a regional hindcast model and a global altimeter wave dataset. This paper also presents the first validation of Deep Learning-derived shorelines using synchronous independent in-situ data. We found the best overall performance and least threshold-sensitive shoreline extraction approach to be the WI index, whilst NDWI had the poorest performances despite being the most utilized across the literature. We found that the thresholdless Unet+++ solution coupled with an ensemble wave run-up model and the altimeter wave data is an adequate trade-off in terms of accuracy, adaptability and wave data access for global scale shoreline studies"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a method for shoreline extraction from satellite imagery, using a machine learning model trained to classify image pixels. The primary ethical considerations arise from the geographic scope of the model's training data and the methods used to evaluate its performance. Specifically, the use of a model trained on data from a single beach (Narrabeen Beach) for validation across fifteen different coastal locations in Victoria, Australia, constitutes a use of unrepresentative geographic training data. Furthermore, the paper's approach to performance evaluation, whether it is spatially aggregated or explicit, is a key technical choice with direct ethical implications for understanding model reliability.\n\nThe audit finds that the paper's methodology instantiates a risk of population bias. Based on moderate-confidence evidence, the use of geographically unrepresentative training data is likely to promote a bias where the model performs differently in the target regions compared to the original training site. While this paper does not deploy its model for downstream tasks, it is important to disclose that this type of population bias can, in the context of land use and resource management, potentially lead to resource allocation inequality. Similarly, the general risk of evaluation bias hiding regional variability can lead to reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions, although this paper does not instantiate this specific impact.\n\nOn the matter of mitigation, the paper takes commendable steps to address evaluation bias. The auditor finds with strong confidence that the paper avoids the risk of hiding regional performance issues by not relying solely on aggregate, non-spatially-explicit metrics like precision and recall. Instead, the paper actively instantiates a mitigation by employing spatially-explicit performance evaluation, using a network of alongshore transects to detect performance hotspots and coldspots. This is a moderately-grounded finding that demonstrates the paper's contribution towards inhibiting evaluation bias. In summary, this audit identifies one instantiated risk of population bias, which is moderately grounded. However, the paper also actively implements a key mitigation against evaluation bias, suggesting a robust approach to understanding spatial performance variability.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | n/a>  (when: When performance is only measured as an aggregate overall score on a corpus)\n- (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the deployment of geoparsers for downstream geospatial tasks)\n- (spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (evaluation bias hiding regional variability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: By exposing where a geoparser is biased towards or against)\n- (unrepresentative geographic training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When datasets fail to represent actual target regions)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the context of land use and resource management)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: non-spatially-explicit evaluation metrics precision recall f-score, unrepresentative geographic training data\n  RiskMechanism: evaluation bias hiding regional variability, population bias\n  EthicalImpact: reduced reliability and fairness in underserved regions, resource allocation inequality\n  Mitigation: spatially-explicit performance evaluation hotcold spot detection",
