     "source": "Transactions in GIS - 2023 - Xing - The challenges of integrating explainable artificial intelligence into GeoAI.pdf",
     "content": "the  results (e.g., classification labels or prediction values) (Lundberg & Lee, 2017). Researchers usually rank resulting  SHAP values to determine key features associated with those values across layers to explain how the object was  classified. SHAP values that present high variance from the same dataset could mean the input data is messy or  that the DNN needs to be tuned. Researchers can utilize the magnitude of SHAP values to optimize the perfor - mance (e.g., weights of individual neurons), providing valuable information for the redesign of DNNs. To build the land use classification DNN, we used a standard training dataset called the University of California  Merced Land Use dataset (UCMLU), which was developed by Yang and Newsam  (2010). The UCMLU dataset con- tains 100 labeled images for each of 21 land use classes, from agricultural to storage tanks to airplanes and run - ways (http://weegee.vision.ucmer  ced.edu/datas ets/landu  se.html). Our land use classification case study was built  with the UCMLU dataset and a model from the University of Oxford Visual Geometry Group (VGG16). VGG16 is  a 16- layer CNN that is widely used for general image classification as well as remote sensing image classification  (Simonyan & Zisserman,  2014). We trained and tested the VGG16 with the UCMLU dataset. Without hyperparam - eter tuning of the VGG16 model, we achieved a classification accuracy of 89.1%. For illustration purposes, we chose one correctly classified example, a runway, and one misclassified example,  an overpass labeled a mobilehomepark. We examined two layers instead of all layers to simplify the discussion   14679671, 2023, 3, Downloaded from https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/tgis.13045, Wiley Online Library on [10/06/2026]. See the Terms and Conditions (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/terms-and-conditions) on Wiley Online Library for rules of use; OA articles are governed by the applicable Creative Commons License 632  |    XING and SIEBER"
