   "source": {
    "title": "Landslide mapping from multi-sensor data through improved change detection-based Markov random field",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2019.111235",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2019.111235",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2019",
    "abstract": "Accurate landslide inventory mapping is essential for quantitative hazard and risk assessment. Although multi-temporal change detection techniques have contributed greatly to landslide inventory preparation, it is still challenging to generate quality change detection images (CDIs) for accurate landslide mapping. The recently proposed change detection-based Markov random field (CDMRF) provides an effective approach for rapid mapping of landslides with minimum user interventions. However, when CDI is generated by change vector analysis (CVA) alone, the CDMRF method may suffer from noise especially when the pre- and post-event remote sensing images are acquired under different atmospheric, illumination, and phenological conditions. This paper improved such CDMRF approach by integrating normalized difference vegetation index (NDVI), principal component analysis (PCA), and independent component analysis (ICA) generated CDIs with MRF for landslide inventory mapping from multi-sensor data. To justify the effectiveness and applicability, the improved methods were applied to map rainfall-, typhoon-, and earthquake-triggered landslides from the pre- and post-event satellite images acquired by very high resolution QuickBird, high resolution FORMOSAT-2, and moderate resolution Sentinel-2. Moreover, they were tested on pre-event Landsat-8 and post-event Sentinel-2 datasets, indicating that they are operational for landslide inventory mapping from combined multi-temporal and multi-sensor "
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a CDMRF framework designed for automated landslide inventory mapping from satellite imagery. The technical contribution lies in its method for automated environmental feature extraction. This automation of a critical mapping task is the primary trigger for the ethical considerations examined in this audit, specifically focusing on the reliability and consequences of the model's classifications.\n\nThe audit identifies one instantiated risk finding. It is plausible that the CDMRF framework promotes inadvertent inferential error, a finding grounded with moderate confidence. This risk is conditional and manifests when the model processes imagery containing spectrally similar but semantically different features, such as mistaking roads for landslide debris due to their similar appearance. The paper's own discussion notes this occurrence, confirming localized over-detection. While not triggered in this paper, such inferential errors can be associated with promoting inequitable social outcomes. In the general case, should such mapping inaccuracies propagate without ethical guides to check data and methods, they could negatively influence crucial resource allocation and land-use planning for vulnerable communities that depend on this information.\n\nThe authors demonstrate an awareness of the inferential error risk and implement a mitigation. To address the specific problem of misclassifying infrastructure, they remove all built-up areas from the bi-temporal images using existing topographic data, which reduces commission errors in those zones. In summary, this audit finds one instantiated risk of inferential error, supported by moderately confident evidence from the paper itself, which the authors have taken steps to partially mitigate. A more severe potential social impact is disclosed as a category-level risk associated with this type of error, but it is not instantiated by the current work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (CDMRF framework for automated landslide inventory mapping:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When spectrally similar but semantically different features (e.g., roads and landslide debris) exist in the imagery.)\n- (inadvertent inferential error:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (inequitable social outcomes:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: In the absence of ethical guides to provide checks and balances on data and methods.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: CDMRF framework for automated landslide inventory mapping\n  RiskMechanism: inadvertent inferential error\n  EthicalImpact: inequitable social outcomes",
