   "id": "096",
   "source": {
    "title": "Effectiveness of machine learning methods for water segmentation with ROI as the label: A case study of the Tuul River in Mongolia",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jag.2021.102497",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jag.2021.102497",
    "journal": "International Journal of Applied Earth Observation and Geoinformation",
    "year": "2021",
    "abstract": "The carrying capacity of water resources is key to the sustainable development of arid and semi-arid regions. There are important challenges related to the detection of discontinuous and crooked water bodies in the vast Mongolian Plateau, despite the availability of remote sensing technology which has the advantage of facilitating water observations over large areas and timelines. Given the high cost and low coverage of high-resolution images and the low resolution of images with high coverage, this study proposes a pixel-based convolutional neural network (CNN) method for the application of water extracted from the region of interest (ROI) to medium-resolution Landsat images. The pixel-based CNN method combines the texture and spectral features of the ground object by connecting the center pixels of the images to the surrounding pixels. ROI is used instead of full-label datasets, reduce the difficulty of building labels in low-to-medium-resolution images. Taking the Tuul River in Mongolia as a case, the pixel-based CNN method, the normalized difference water index threshold (NDWI) method, the modified normalized difference water index (MNDWI) threshold method, U-net model in deep learning, and the pixel-based deep neural network (DNN) method were used with medium-resolution Landsat 8 images with ROI labels. The pixel-based CNN method shows better water extraction results for the cloud, cloud shadows, and building areas, compared with other methods. The method proposed in thi"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents a method for water body mapping using a Pixel-based Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) trained on sparse Region of Interest (ROI) labels. The primary ethical touchpoints identified in this audit relate to the technical choices of the model architecture and the data sampling strategy. Specifically, the use of a CNN to process complex, multidimensional geographic variables introduces considerations of algorithmic transparency. Furthermore, the reliance on an ROI-based labeling approach, intended to reduce the difficulty of creating training data, triggers an examination of potential geographic representation bias.\n\nThe audit identifies two instantiated risks based on the paper's methodology. First, the use of a pixel-based CNN to process combined texture and spectral features plausibly promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, particularly when complex variables are handled without transparent guardrails. Second, the strategy of training the model on sparse ROI labels gives rise to a moderate potential for geographic representation bias, which can occur when the ROI selection strategy does not ensure representative sampling across diverse landscapes. In addition to these findings, the audit discloses potential downstream impacts associated with these types of methods. A lack of transparency can lead to safety risks in critical missions, a concern when such models are applied to high-risk applications like the disaster management scenarios mentioned by the authors. Similarly, geographic representation bias could potentially lead to an unequal quality of water mapping services across different areas, though this latter connection is a tentative inference. It is important to note that these downstream impacts are disclosed as category-level risks and were not found to be directly instantiated by this paper's specific implementation.\n\nThe paper provides one significant mitigation that directly addresses the transparency concern. The authors' choice to pursue an open-source release of their models and code serves to inhibit the lack of algorithmic transparency by allowing for independent scrutiny, replication, and testing of the model's behavior. In summary, this audit identifies two moderately-grounded risks that are instantiated by the paper's methodology—one concerning transparency and another concerning representational bias. The transparency risk is partially offset by the open-source release mitigation. The more severe potential societal impacts remain disclosures of risks associated with this class of technology rather than direct findings against this specific work.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (Pixel-based Convolutional Neural Network (CNN):TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (Lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When complex multidimensional geographic variables are processed without transparent guardrails.)\n- (Lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (Safety risks in critical missions:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When applied to high-risk remote sensing applications like disaster management.)\n- (Open-source release of models and code:Mitigation) --INHIBITS--> (Lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: By allowing for independent scrutiny, replication, and testing of the model's behavior.)\n- (Training model on sparse Region of Interest (ROI) labels:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (Geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When the ROI selection strategy does not ensure representative geographic sampling across diverse landscapes (e.g., urban, rural, agricultural).)\n- (Geographic representation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (Unequal quality of water mapping services:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <inferred | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When model performance varies across different parts of a study area due to unrepresentative training data.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: Pixel-based Convolutional Neural Network (CNN), Training model on sparse Region of Interest (ROI) labels\n  RiskMechanism: Lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, Geographic representation bias\n  EthicalImpact: Safety risks in critical missions, Unequal quality of water mapping services\n  Mitigation: Open-source release of models and code",
