   "id": "099",
   "source": {
    "title": "DPF-Net: Physical imaging model embedded data-driven underwater image enhancement",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2025.07.031",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.isprsjprs.2025.07.031",
    "journal": "ISPRS Journal of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing",
    "year": "2025",
    "abstract": "Due to the complex interplay of light absorption and scattering in the underwater environment, underwater images experience significant degradation. This research presents a two-stage underwater image enhancement network called the Data-Driven and Physical Parameters Fusion Network (DPF-Net), which harnesses the robustness of physical imaging models alongside the generality and efficiency of data-driven methods. We train the Degraded Parameters Estimation Module (DPEM) on synthetic datasets with preset physical parameters as ground truth. This approach learns more authentic underwater imaging model, contrasting with prior works that directly fit raw-to-reference image mappings through the imaging equation. This module is subsequently trained in conjunction with an enhancement network, where the estimated physical parameters are integrated into a data-driven model within the embedding space. During model training, in addition to traditional reference-based losses, we use a degradation consistency loss to ensure physical consistency. Furthermore, we propose a new weak reference loss term that leverages the color distribution of the entire training set, thereby alleviating the reliance of our model on the quality of individual reference images. Our proposed DPF-Net demonstrates superior performance compared to other benchmark methods across multiple test sets, achieving state-of-the-art results. The source code and pre-trained models are available on the project home page: https"
   },
   "report": "This paper presents DPF-Net, a two-stage network for underwater image enhancement that combines data-driven methods with physical imaging models. The primary ethical touchpoints of this work originate from its technical design. As a form of `process automation with reduced human intervention`, the network is designed to automate a crucial pre-processing step for various downstream applications. A second key feature is the model's reliance on specific training data, including an indoor dataset (NYU-Depth-V2) used to synthesize underwater degradation and the UIEB underwater image benchmark, which raises the issue of potentially `unrepresentative geographic training data`.\n\nThe audit's central finding, supported with moderate confidence, is that the paper's methodology instantiates a risk of `algorithmic bias`. This is promoted by the use of `unrepresentative geographic training data`, as the model is trained on a finite set of environments and may not generalize effectively when deployed in novel aquatic settings with different optical properties. In addition to this instantiated risk, the audit discloses several potential risks associated with this class of technology but not triggered by this paper's specific actions. The automation of image enhancement strongly suggests a potential for `automation bias`, particularly if the network is used as a primary analysis tool without sufficient human oversight. This, in turn, could lead to `misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data` in high-stakes applications or `resource allocation inequality` if biased outputs inform marine resource management, though these are downstream impacts not realized within the scope of this work.\n\nThe provided information does not describe any mitigations to address the identified risks. The overall judgement is that this paper instantiates one primary ethical risk—`algorithmic bias`—which is grounded with moderate confidence and is conditional on the model's deployment in environments dissimilar to its training data. Several other serious risks, including those related to `automation bias`, are noted as disclosures relevant to this technological category but are not directly triggered by the paper's contribution.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (process automation with reduced human intervention:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (automation bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | disclosure>  (when: When an automated image enhancement network is used as a primary tool for analysis without sufficient human oversight.)\n- (automation bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data:EthicalImpact) [PhysicalHarm]  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When operators over-rely on algorithmically enhanced imagery for high-stakes, time-sensitive tasks where visual errors could have catastrophic consequences.)\n- (unrepresentative geographic training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When the model is trained on a finite set of underwater environments and then deployed in novel aquatic settings with different optical properties.)\n- (algorithmic bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EconomicLoss]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When biased image enhancement quality (e.g., performing better in water types seen during training) is used to inform surveys for marine resource management across diverse regions.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: process automation with reduced human intervention, unrepresentative geographic training data\n  RiskMechanism: automation bias, algorithmic bias\n  EthicalImpact: misinterpretation or misuse of remote sensing data, resource allocation inequality",
