   "source": {
    "title": "Monthly monitoring of urban development and renewal at the block-level in China using Sentinel-2 time series",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.rse.2025.115070",
    "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2025.115070",
    "journal": "Remote Sensing of Environment",
    "year": "2026",
    "abstract": "Urban renewal has been elevated to a national strategy in China, leading to rapid development and transformation of street blocks. However, monitoring construction events at high temporal resolution remains challenging due to the limitations of existing methods, which often struggle with noise interference and lack continuous monitoring capabilities. To address this, we propose Semantic Similarity Contrast-based Street Block Monitoring (SSC-SB), a method that leverages Sentinel-2 time series imagery for automated, high-frequency detection of street block development and renewal. By extracting deep semantic features with a pretrained encoder, SSC-SB analyzes similarity curves to identify development and demolition construction events. Applied to the Middle Yangtze River Basin (MYRB) urban agglomeration shows that SSC-SB achieves 90.4% spatial domain accuracy, with construction start and end date detection accuracies of 68.8% and 54.9%, respectively. Results indicate an increasing emphasis on urban renewal, as demolished street blocks outnumbered new developments for the first time in 2023, with Hunan Province leading in renewal efforts, where renewal blocks accounted for 41.5% of all changed street blocks, reflecting a balanced focus on expansion and infrastructure renewal. Transfer experiments in Xi’an further demonstrate that SSC-SB retains up to 80% of the performance of a locally trained model when applied across regions without fine-tuning, indicating a decent level of ge"
   },
   "report": "This paper develops a model for monitoring urban renewal, employing a deep semantic encoder architecture based on ResNet18 and a supervised contrastive learning paradigm. The ethical dimensions of this work are triggered by three specific aspects of its methodology. First, the use of a deep learning model for a high-stakes civic application raises questions of transparency. Second, the supervised learning approach itself creates the conditions for performance disparities across different monitored classes. Finally, the paper’s experimental design involves applying a model trained on unrepresentative geographic data from one urban agglomeration to a different city, directly engaging with issues of geographic bias.\n\nBased on the evidence, this audit finds several instantiated ethical risks. There is a strong finding that the use of unrepresentative geographic training data promotes population bias; this is demonstrated when the paper’s model, trained in the Middle Yangtze River Basin, is applied to Xi'an without fine-tuning, resulting in a performance drop. The audit also finds plausible, moderately-grounded evidence for two other risks. The choice of a deep semantic encoder architecture promotes a lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, a significant concern when using such a model for a high-stakes civic application without implementing explainability methods. Additionally, the supervised contrastive learning paradigm appears to instantiate an algorithmic focus bias, conditional on the model's accuracy being significantly lower for subtle but critical stages of urban renewal, which is evidenced by the reported 54.9% accuracy for project completion versus 68.8% for project start. While the paper does not instantiate their downstream consequences, it is important to disclose that these types of risks can lead to significant societal impacts; for instance, a geographically biased tool could promote resource allocation inequality, an opaque model could lead to social inequity when auditing policy for vulnerable communities, and an algorithmic focus bias could result in the unfair distribution of urban resources if the tool were used to guide municipal planning.\n\nIn summary, this audit identifies three ethical risks as being instantiated by the paper’s contribution, with no specific mitigations for them noted in the provided material. The finding of population bias is strongly supported by the paper’s own cross-regional transfer experiments. The findings related to a lack of algorithmic transparency and an algorithmic focus bias are moderately grounded in the choice of model architecture and the reported performance metrics, respectively. The analysis also serves to disclose several potential, but not triggered, downstream harms related to social and resource inequity, highlighting areas for consideration if this type of technology were to be deployed for decision-making.\n\n---\nAppendix: structured audit triples\n\nGeoAI Ethics Audit Report (triple-based)\n\n- (unrepresentative geographic training data:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (population bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_exact | quote✓ | AUDIT>  (when: When a model trained in one urban agglomeration (MYRB) is applied to another (Xi'an) without fine-tuning.)\n- (population bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (resource allocation inequality:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When a geographically biased monitoring tool is used to inform planning and resource allocation decisions.)\n- (deep semantic encoder architecture:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When using a deep learning model (ResNet18) for a high-stakes civic application without implementing explainability methods.)\n- (lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (social inequity:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When an opaque model is used to audit policy compliance for vulnerable communities like 'urban villages'.)\n- (supervised contrastive learning paradigm:TechnicalFeature) --PROMOTES--> (algorithmic focus bias:RiskMechanism)  <graph_anchored | quote✗ | AUDIT>  (when: When model accuracy is significantly lower for subtle but critical stages of urban renewal, such as project completion.)\n- (algorithmic focus bias:RiskMechanism) --PROMOTES--> (unfair distribution of urban resources and services:EthicalImpact) [EqualRightsViolation]  <graph_exact | quote✗ | disclosure>  (when: When a biased monitoring tool is used to track infrastructure projects and guide municipal planning.)\n\nEntities by type:\n  TechnicalFeature: unrepresentative geographic training data, deep semantic encoder architecture, supervised contrastive learning paradigm\n  RiskMechanism: population bias, lack of algorithmic transparency and explainability, algorithmic focus bias\n  EthicalImpact: resource allocation inequality, social inequity, unfair distribution of urban resources and services",
